# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: endangered-mammals-of-india
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The **cheetah** (***Acinonyx jubatus***) is a species of large feline and the only living member of the genus *Acinonyx*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah is a pursuit predator and the fastest land animal, capable of running at 93–104 km/h (58–65 mph); it has evolved for speed, having powerful hindlimb muscles, long limbs and a flexible spine.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah has a tawny to creamy white or pale buff fur that is marked with evenly spaced, solid black spots.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The head is small and rounded, with a short snout and black tear-like facial streaks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It reaches 67–94 cm (2.20–3.08 ft) at the shoulder, and the head-and-body length is between 1.1 and 1.5 m (3 ft 7 in and 4 ft 11 in).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Adults weigh between 21 and 65 kg (46 and 143 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah was first scientifically described in the late 18th century.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Four subspecies are recognised today that are native to Africa and central Iran.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] An African subspecies was introduced to India in 2022.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It is now distributed mainly in small, fragmented populations in northwestern, eastern and southern Africa and central Iran.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It lives in a variety of habitats such as savannahs in the Serengeti, arid mountain ranges in the Sahara, and hilly desert terrain.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah lives in three main social groups: females and their cubs, male "coalitions", and solitary males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] While females lead a nomadic life searching for prey in large home ranges, males are more sedentary and instead establish much smaller territories in areas with plentiful prey and access to females.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah is active during the day, with peaks during dawn and dusk.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It feeds on small- to medium-sized prey, mostly weighing under 40 kg (88 lb), and prefers medium-sized ungulates such as impala, springbok and Thomson's gazelles.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah typically stalks and approaches its prey within 30–200 m (98–656 ft) before charging at high speed, striking down the prey with its dewclaw in full pursuit and killing it with a throat bite.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] After a gestation of nearly three months, females give birth to a litter of three or four cubs, who are weaned at around four months and are independent by around 20 months of age.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cheetah cubs are highly vulnerable to predation by other large carnivores such as lions and hyenas, who also routinely steal kills from adult cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah is threatened by habitat loss, conflict with humans, poaching and high susceptibility to diseases.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The global cheetah population was estimated at 6,517 individuals in 2021; it is listed as Vulnerable on the IUCN Red List.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It has been widely depicted in art, literature, advertising, and animation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Although not usually considered a target of domestication, the cheetah had been tamed in ancient Egypt and trained for hunting ungulates in the Arabian Peninsula and India, and has been kept in zoos since the early 19th century.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The vernacular name "cheetah" is derived from Hindustani Urdu: چیتا and Hindi: चीता (*ćītā*).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] This in turn comes from Sanskrit: चित्रय (*Chitra-ya*) meaning 'variegated', 'adorned' or 'painted'.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In the past, the cheetah was often called "hunting leopard" because they could be tamed and used for coursing.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The generic name *Acinonyx* probably derives from the combination of two Greek words: ἀκίνητος (*akī́nētos*) meaning 'unmoved' or 'motionless', and ὄνυξ (*ónyx*) meaning 'nail' or 'hoof'.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A rough translation is "immobile nails", a reference to the cheetah's limited ability to retract its claws.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A similar meaning can be obtained by the combination of the Greek prefix *a–* (implying a lack of) and κῑνέω (*kīnéō*) meaning 'to move' or 'to set in motion'.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The specific name *jubatus* is Latin for 'crested, having a mane'.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A few old generic names such as *Cynailurus* and *Cynofelis* allude to the similarities between the cheetah and canids.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 1777, Johann Christian Daniel von Schreber described the cheetah based on a skin from the Cape of Good Hope and gave it the scientific name *Felis jubatus*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Joshua Brookes proposed the generic name *Acinonyx* in 1828.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 1917, Reginald Innes Pocock placed the cheetah in a subfamily of its own, Acinonychinae, given its striking morphological resemblance to the greyhound and significant deviation from typical felid features; the cheetah was classified in Felinae in later taxonomic revisions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In the 19th and 20th centuries, several cheetah zoological specimens were described; some were proposed as subspecies.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A South African specimen with notably dense fur was proposed as (*Felis lanea*) by Philip Sclater in 1877 and became known as the "woolly cheetah".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Its classification as a species was mostly disputed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] There has been considerable confusion in the nomenclature of the cheetah and leopard (*Panthera pardus*) as authors often confused the two; some considered "hunting leopards" an independent species, or equal to the leopard.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 1975, five cheetah subspecies were considered valid taxa: *A. j. hecki*, *A. j. jubatus*, *A. j. raineyi*, *A. j. soemmeringii* and *A. j. venaticus*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 2011, a phylogeographic study found minimal genetic variation between *A. j. jubatus* and *A. j. raineyi*; only four subspecies were identified.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 2017, the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group revised felid taxonomy and recognised these four subspecies as valid.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah's closest relatives are the cougar (*Puma concolor*) and the jaguarundi (*Herpailurus yagouaroundi*).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Together, these three species form the *Puma* lineage, one of the eight lineages of the extant felids; the *Puma* lineage genetically diverged from the rest 6.7 million years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The sister group of the *Puma* lineage is a clade of smaller Old World cats that includes the genera *Felis*, *Otocolobus* and *Prionailurus*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The oldest cheetah fossils, excavated in eastern and southern Africa, date to 3.5 to 3 million years ago; the earliest known specimen from South Africa is from the lowermost deposits of the Silberberg Grotto (Sterkfontein).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Though incomplete, these fossils indicate forms larger but less cursorial than the modern cheetah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The first occurrence of the modern species *A. jubatus* in Africa may come from Cooper's D, a site in South Africa dating back to 1.5 to 1.4 million years ago, during the Calabrian stage.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Fossil remains from Europe are limited to a few Middle Pleistocene specimens from Hundsheim (Austria) and Mosbach Sands (Germany).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cheetah-like cats are known from as late as 10,000 years ago from the Old World.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The giant cheetah (*A. pardinensis*), significantly larger and slower compared to the modern cheetah, occurred in Eurasia and eastern and southern Africa in the Villafranchian period roughly 3.8 to 1.9 million years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In the Middle Pleistocene a smaller cheetah, *A. intermedius*, ranged from Europe to China.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The modern cheetah appeared in Africa around 1.9 million years ago; its fossil record is restricted to Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Extinct North American cheetah-like cats had historically been classified in *Felis*, *Puma* or *Acinonyx*; two such species, *F. studeri* and *F. trumani*, were considered to be closer to the puma than the cheetah, despite their close similarities to the latter.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Noting this, palaeontologist Daniel Adams proposed *Miracinonyx*, a new subgenus under *Acinonyx*, in 1979 for the North American cheetah-like cats; this was later elevated to genus rank.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Adams pointed out that North American and Old World cheetah-like cats may have had a common ancestor, and *Acinonyx* might have originated in North America instead of Eurasia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] However, subsequent research has shown that *Miracinonyx* is phylogenetically closer to the cougar than the cheetah; the similarities to cheetahs have been attributed to parallel evolution.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The three species of the *Puma* lineage may have had a common ancestor during the Miocene, roughly 8.25 million years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The diploid number of chromosomes in the cheetah is 38, the same as in most other felids.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah was the first felid observed to have unusually low genetic variability among individuals, which has led to poor breeding in captivity, increased spermatozoal defects, high juvenile mortality and increased susceptibility to diseases and infections.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A prominent instance was the deadly feline coronavirus outbreak in the cheetah breeding facility at Wildlife Safari in Winston, Oregon in 1983 which had a mortality rate of 60%, higher than that recorded for previous epizootics of feline infectious peritonitis in any felid.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The remarkable homogeneity in cheetah genes has been demonstrated by experiments involving the major histocompatibility complex (MHC); unless the MHC genes are highly homogeneous in a population, skin grafts exchanged between a pair of unrelated individuals would be rejected.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Skin grafts exchanged between unrelated cheetahs are accepted well and heal, as if their genetic makeup were the same.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The low genetic diversity is thought to have been created by two population bottlenecks from about 100,000 years and about 12,000 years ago, respectively.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The resultant level of genetic variation is around 0.1–4% of average living species, lower than that of Tasmanian devils, Virunga gorillas, Amur tigers, and even highly inbred domestic cats and dogs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The king cheetah is a variety of cheetah with a rare mutation for cream-coloured fur marked with large, blotchy spots and three dark, wide stripes extending from the neck to the tail.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In Manicaland, Zimbabwe, it was known as *nsuifisi* and thought to be a cross between a leopard and a hyena.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cooper wrote about a cheetah-like animal he had shot near modern-day Harare, with fur as thick as that of a snow leopard and spots that merged to form stripes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] He suggested it could be a cross between a leopard and a cheetah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] As more such individuals were observed it was seen that they had non-retractable claws like the cheetah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 1927, Pocock described these individuals as a new species by the name of *Acinonyx rex* ("king cheetah").
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] However, in the absence of proof to support his claim, he withdrew his proposal in 1939.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Abel Chapman considered it a colour morph of the normally spotted cheetah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Since 1927, the king cheetah has been reported five more times in the wild in Zimbabwe, Botswana and northern Transvaal; one was photographed in 1975.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 1981, two female cheetahs that had mated with a wild male from Transvaal at the De Wildt Cheetah and Wildlife Centre (South Africa) gave birth to one king cheetah each; subsequently, more king cheetahs were born at the centre.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 2012, the cause of this coat pattern was found to be a mutation in the gene for transmembrane aminopeptidase (Taqpep), the same gene responsible for the striped "mackerel" versus blotchy "classic" pattern seen in tabby cats.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The appearance is caused by reinforcement of a recessive allele; hence if two mating cheetahs are heterozygous carriers of the mutated allele, a quarter of their offspring can be expected to be king cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah is a slim-bodied, spotted cat characterised by a small, streamlined head, a short snout, black tear-like facial streaks, a deep chest, long limbs and a long tail.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Its slim, canid-like form is highly adapted for running, and contrasts sharply with the bulky body of the *Panthera* genus members and cougars.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cheetahs typically reach 67–94 cm (2.20–3.08 ft) at the shoulder and the head-and-body length is between 1.1 and 1.5 m (3 ft 7 in and 4 ft 11 in).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The weight can vary with age, health, location, sex and subspecies; adults typically range between 21 and 65 kg (46 and 143 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cubs born in the wild weigh 150–300 g (5.3–10.6 oz) at birth, while those born in captivity tend to be larger and weigh around 500 g (18 oz).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah is sexually dimorphic; females are smaller than males in average.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Studies differ significantly on morphological variations among the subspecies.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah's coat is typically tawny to creamy white or pale buff, but darker in the mid-back portion.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The chin, throat and underparts of the legs and the belly are white and devoid of markings.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The rest of the body is covered with around 2,000 evenly spaced, oval or round solid black spots, each measuring roughly 3–5 cm (1.2–2.0 in).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Each cheetah has a distinct pattern of spots which can be used to identify unique individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Besides the clearly visible spots, there are other faint, irregular black marks on the coat.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Newly born cubs are covered in fur with an unclear pattern of spots that gives them a dark appearance—pale white above and nearly black on the underside.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The hair is mostly short and often coarse, but the chest and the belly are covered in soft fur; the fur of king cheetahs has been reported to be silky.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] There is a short, rough mane, covering at least 8 cm (3.1 in) along the neck and the shoulders; this feature is more prominent in males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The mane starts out as a cape of long, loose blue to grey hair in juveniles.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Melanistic cheetahs are rare and have been seen in Zambia and Zimbabwe.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 1877–1878, two partially albino specimens from South Africa were described.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A tabby cheetah was photographed in Kenya in 2012.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Saharan cheetahs have canid-like slim faces.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The ears are small, short and rounded; they are tawny at the base and on the edges and marked with black patches on the back.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The eyes are set high and have round pupils.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The pronounced tear streaks are unique to the cheetah and originate from the corners of the eyes and run down the nose to the mouth.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The role of these streaks is not well understood, they may protect the eyes from the sun's glare or could be used to define facial expressions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The whiskers, shorter and fewer than those of other felids, are fine and inconspicuous.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The long tail, with a bushy white tuft at the end, measures 60–80 cm (24–31 in).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] While the first two-thirds of the tail are covered in spots, the final third is marked with four to six dark rings or stripes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Although similar at first glance, the leopard has rosettes instead of spots and does not have tear streaks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The serval also resembles the cheetah, but its spots fuse to form stripes on the back.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah has a physiology specialised for sprinting; its thigh muscles are 50% heavier than predicted for quadrupedal mammals of the same body mass, while those of a lion or tiger closes to what is predicted for their body mass.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It has a concentration of type IIx muscle fibers of 50.1% in the hindlimbs, 40% in the neck and trunk, and 36% in the forelimbs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Betz cells in primary motor cortex are exceptionally large for its brain mass and would be to innervate more type IIx muscle fibers and larger locomotor muscles.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah cannot utilise oxygen at the same level as other mammals; its mitochondrial volume represents only 3.7% of the total volume of the muscle fibers, compared to 6.5–10.7% in dogs and ponies.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah has the largest frontal sinuses among felids, which may help it to cool the air that it breathes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The average temperature of a few cheetahs measured after hunts is 38.6 °C (101.5 °F), suggesting that intense physical activity does not cause overheating.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The slightly curved claws are shorter and straighter than those of other cats, lack a protective sheath and are partly retractile.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The limited retraction of claws may result from the earlier truncation of the development of the cheetah's middle phalanx bone.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The claws are blunt due to lack of protection.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] But the large and strongly curved dewclaw is sharp.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah has relatively the largest shoulder retractor, shoulder extensor and elbow extensor muscles among felids.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The extension of its stride comes mainly from the flexion of the spine before the feet strike the ground during air suspension phases.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Its flexed trunk length represents only 67% of its extended trunk length, compared to 80–90% of a horse.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah lumbar region is the longest among carnivore mammals, accounting for half of the combined length of its spine's thoracic and lumbar regions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah's tail does not serve as counterbalance, as it represents only 2% of its body mass, thereby not providing significant moment of inertia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah's tail serves as a rudder, as the thick fur increases its effective area by 40%, thereby increasing aerodynamic drag.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The tail performs rotational movements that could reach angular velocities of 17–22 radians per second and angles of 90°.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The roughly triangular skull has light, narrow bones, and the sagittal crest is poorly developed, possibly to reduce weight and enhance speed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The mouth can not be opened as widely as in other cats given the shorter length of muscles between the jaw and the skull.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The small, conical canines are used to bite the throat and suffocate the prey.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah jaws generate the highest bite force in canine teeth among felids at 689 Newtons, when all skulls are scaled to the same surface area of 1.42×105 mm2 and all muscles generate the same force of 871 Newtons; cheetah jaws can distribute the mechanical stress efficiently.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Its canines have no diastema behind them when the jaws close, as the top and bottom cheek teeth show extensive overlap.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah has relatively elongated and blade-like shape carnassial teeth, with reduced lingual cusps, which is thought to be an adaptation to quickly consume the flesh of prey before larger predators arrive.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah is the fastest land animal, capable of overtaking pronghorns and fast antelopes, even when they have a 137 m (449 ft) head start.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cheetahs can easily outrun greyhounds in a race.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A popular figure of 114 km/h (71 mph) has been discredited due to a faulty measurement method.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The highest reliably reported running speed is 104 km/h (65 mph).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A speed of 100.1 km/h (62.2 mph) also has been reliably reported.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] An 11-year-old cheetah from the Cincinnati Zoo set a record by running at a maximum speed of 98 km/h (61 mph).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cheetahs equipped with GPS collars hunted at speeds lower than the highest speeds attained; the average running speed recorded during hunts was 54 km/h (34 mph), while the highest speed recorded was 93 km/h (58 mph).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah uses its maximum running speed only to close the distance with the prey in a straight line, then it follows closely during 3–4 twists in zigzag that the prey makes trying to escape.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The speeds of more than 100 km/h (62 mph) attained by the cheetah are greater than those achieved typically by the pronghorn and fast antelopes at 80 km/h (50 mph).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] But the cheetah has an exceptional acceleration, from 0 to 97 km/h (0 to 60 mph) in less than 3 seconds.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] For comparison, polo horses can go from 0 to 36 km/h (0 to 22 mph) in 3.6 seconds.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] One stride of a galloping cheetah measures 4 to 7 m (13 to 23 ft); the stride length and the number of jumps increases with speed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The movements of the vertebral column can add as much as 76 cm (2.49 ft) to the stride length.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It has been estimated that a cheetah at full speed could take 4 strides per second.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] During more than half the duration of the sprint, the cheetah has all four limbs in the air, increasing the stride length.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In eastern and southern Africa, the cheetah occurs mostly in savannas like the Kalahari and Serengeti.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In central, northern and western Africa, it inhabits arid mountain ranges and valleys; in the harsh climate of the Sahara, it prefers high mountains, which receive more rainfall than the surrounding desert.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The vegetation and water resources in these mountains support antelopes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In Iran, it occurs in hilly terrain of deserts at elevations up to 2,000–3,000 m (6,600–9,800 ft), where annual precipitation is generally below 100 mm (3.9 in); the primary vegetation in these areas is thinly distributed shrubs, less than 1 m (3 ft 3 in) tall.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah inhabits a variety of ecosystems and appears to be less selective in habitat choice than other felids; it prefers areas with greater availability of prey, good visibility and minimal chances of encountering larger predators.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] It has been reported at the elevation of 4,000 m (13,000 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] An open area with some cover, such as diffused bushes, is probably ideal for the cheetah because it needs to stalk and pursue its prey over a distance.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] This also minimises the risk of encountering larger carnivores.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah tends to occur in low densities typically between 0.3 and 3.0 adults per 100 km2 (39 sq mi); these values are 10–30% of those reported for leopards and lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In prehistoric times, the cheetah was distributed throughout Africa, Western and Central Asia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Today the cheetah has been extirpated in most of its historical range; the numbers of the Asiatic cheetah had begun plummeting since the late 1800s, long before the other subspecies started their decline.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] As of 2017, cheetahs occur in just nine per cent of their erstwhile range in Africa, mostly in unprotected areas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Until the mid-20th century, the cheetah ranged across vast stretches in Asia, from the Arabian Peninsula in the west to the Indian subcontinent in the east, and as far north as the Aral and Caspian Seas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] A few centuries ago the cheetah was abundant in India, and its range coincided with the distribution of major prey like the blackbuck.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] However, its numbers in India plummeted from the 19th century onward; the last three wild individuals were killed by Maharaja Ramanuj Pratap Singh of Surguja in 1947.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The last confirmed sighting in India was of a cheetah that drowned in a well near Hyderabad in 1957.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah's range in the Soviet Union encompassed the "desert plains of Middle Asia and southern Kazakhstan and the eastern Trans-Caucasus".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] During the Middle Ages, the cheetah ranged as far as western Georgia and probably survived in the Kura-Aras lowland and central Aras River valley until the 18th century, though it went extinct in the region following the decline of goitered gazelles and due to human persecution.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] By the mid-20th century, the cheetah was reportedly "still quite extensively if sparsely distributed throughout the region west of the Amu Darya and Aral Sea, but has been vanishing very rapidly".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In Iraq, cheetahs were reported from Basra in the 1920s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In Iran there were around 400 cheetahs before World War II, distributed across deserts and steppes to the east and the borderlands with Iraq to the west; the numbers were falling because of a decline in prey.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Conservation efforts in the 1950s stabilised the population, but prey species declined again in the wake of the Iranian Revolution after 1979 and the Iran–Iraq War, leading to a significant contraction of the cheetah's historical range in the region.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In 1975, the cheetah population was estimated at 15,000 individuals throughout Sub-Saharan Africa, following the first survey in this region by Norman Myers.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The range covered most of eastern and southern Africa, except for the desert region on the western coast of modern-day Angola and Namibia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] In the following years, cheetah populations across the region have become smaller and more fragmented as the natural habitat has been modified significantly.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Cheetah mummies dating back to 4223–127 YBP have been found in a cave system in Saudi Arabia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The cheetah occurs mostly in eastern and southern Africa; its presence in Asia is limited to the central deserts of Iran, though there have been unconfirmed reports of sightings in Afghanistan, Iraq and Pakistan in the last few decades.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The global population of cheetahs was estimated at nearly 7,100 mature individuals in 2016.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The Iranian population appears to have decreased from 60 to 100 individuals in 2007 to 43 in 2016, distributed in three subpopulations over less than 150,000 km2 (58,000 sq mi) in Iran's central plateau.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] The largest population of nearly 4,000 individuals is sparsely distributed over Angola, Botswana, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa and Zambia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Another population in Kenya and Tanzania comprises about 1,000 individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] All other cheetahs occur in small, fragmented groups of less than 100 individuals each.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p01] Populations are thought to be declining.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs are active mainly during the day, whereas that competitors such as spotted hyenas and lions are active mainly at night.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] These larger carnivores can kill cheetahs and steal their kills; hence, the diurnal tendency of cheetahs helps them avoid larger predators in areas where they are sympatric, such as the Okavango Delta.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In areas where the cheetah is the major predator (such as farmlands in Botswana and Namibia), activity tends to increase at night.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] This may also happen in highly arid regions such as the Sahara, where daytime temperatures can reach 43 °C (109 °F).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The lunar cycle can also influence the cheetah's routine—activity might increase on moonlit nights as prey can be sighted easily, though this comes with the danger of encountering larger predators.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Hunting is the major activity throughout the day, with peaks during dawn and dusk.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Groups rest in grassy clearings after dusk.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs often inspect their vicinity at observation points such as elevations to check for prey or larger carnivores; even while resting, they take turns at keeping a lookout.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah has a flexible and complex social structure and tends to be more gregarious than other cat species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Individuals typically avoid one another but are generally amicable; males may fight over territories or access to females in oestrus, and on rare occasions such fights can result in severe injury and death.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Females are not social and have minimal interaction with other individuals, barring the interaction with males when they enter their territories or during the mating season.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Some females, generally mother and offspring or siblings, may rest beside one another during the day.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Females tend to lead a solitary life or live with offspring in undefended home ranges; young females often stay close to their mothers for life but young males leave their mother's range to live elsewhere.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Some males are territorial, and group together for life, forming coalitions that collectively defend a territory which ensures maximum access to females—this is unlike the behaviour of the male lion who mates with a particular group (pride) of females.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In most cases, a coalition will consist of brothers born in the same litter who stayed together after weaning, but biologically unrelated males are often allowed into the group; in the Serengeti, 30% of members in coalitions are unrelated males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] If a cub is the only male in a litter, he will typically join an existing group, or form a small group of solitary males with two or three other lone males who may or may not be territorial.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In the Kalahari Desert around 40% of the males live in solitude.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Males in a coalition are affectionate toward each other, grooming mutually and calling out if any member is lost; unrelated males may face some aversion in their initial days in the group.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] All males in the coalition typically have equal access to kills when the group hunts together, and possibly also to females who may enter their territory.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A coalition generally has a greater chance of encountering and acquiring females for mating; however, its large membership demands greater resources than do solitary males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A 1987 study showed that solitary and grouped males have a nearly equal chance of coming across females, but the males in coalitions are notably healthier and have better chances of survival than their solitary counterparts.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Male cheetahs seem to be more tolerant to cubs that are not their offspring than other felids, and supposed evidence of infanticide is considered circumstantial.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Female cheetahs tend to occupy larger home ranges than males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Females typically disperse over large areas in pursuit of prey, but are less nomadic and roam in a smaller area if prey availability in the area is high.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The size of their home range depends on the distribution of prey in a region.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In central Namibia, where most prey species are sparsely distributed, home ranges are 554–7,063 km2 (214–2,727 sq mi), whereas home ranges in the woodlands of Phinda Game Reserve are 34–157 km2 (13–61 sq mi) in size.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs can travel long stretches overland in search of food; a study in the Kalahari Desert recorded an average displacement of nearly 11 km (6.8 mi) every day and walking speeds ranged between 2.5 and 3.8 km/h (1.6 and 2.4 mph).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Males are generally less nomadic than females; often males in coalitions and sometimes solitary males staying far from coalitions establish home ranges.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Whether males settle in territories or disperse over large areas forming home ranges depends primarily on the movements of females.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Territoriality is preferred only if females tend to be more sedentary, which is more feasible in areas with plenty of prey.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Some males, called floaters, switch between territoriality and nomadism depending on the availability of females.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A 1987 study showed territoriality depended on the size and age of males and the membership of the coalition.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The ranges of floaters averaged 777 km2 (300 sq mi) in the Serengeti to 1,464 km2 (565 sq mi) in central Namibia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Territories in Kruger National Park were much smaller.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A coalition of three males occupied a territory of 126 km2 (49 sq mi), and the territory of a solitary male measured 195 km2 (75 sq mi).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] When a female enters a territory, the males surround her; if she tries to escape, the males bite or snap at her.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Generally, the female can not escape on her own; the males themselves leave after they lose interest in her.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] They may smell the spot she was sitting or lying on to determine if she was in oestrus.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah is a vocal felid with a broad repertoire of calls and sounds; the acoustic features and the use of many of these have been studied in detail.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The way vocalisations are produced have some differences compared to the domestic cat, such as cheetah exhalations are louder.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Another major means of communication is by scent; the male often raises his tail and spray urine on elevated landmarks such as a tree trunks, stumps or rocks; other cheetahs sniff these landmarks and repeat the ritual.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Females also show marking behaviour but less prominently than males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Females in oestrus show maximum urine-marking, and their excrement can attract males from far off.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In Botswana, cheetahs are frequently captured by ranchers to protect livestock by setting up traps in traditional marking spots; the calls of the trapped cheetah can attract more cheetahs to the place.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Camera traps at scent-marking sites in north-central Namibia documented that cheetahs defecate on marking sites much more frequently than leopards.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Touch and visual cues are other ways of signalling, and social meetings involve mutual sniffing of the mouth, anus and genitals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Individuals groom one another, lick each other's faces and rub cheeks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] However, they seldom lean on or rub their flanks against each other.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The tear streaks on the face can sharply define expressions at close range.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Mothers probably use the alternate light and dark rings on the tail to signal their cubs to follow them.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah is a carnivore that hunts small to medium prey weighing 20 to 60 kg (44 to 132 lb), but mostly less than 40 kg (88 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Its primary prey are medium-sized ungulates.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] They are the major component of diet in certain areas, such as Dama and Dorcas gazelles in the Sahara, impala in the eastern and southern African woodlands, springbok in the arid savannas to the south and Thomson's gazelle in the Serengeti.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Smaller antelopes like the common duiker are frequent prey in the southern Kalahari.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Larger ungulates are typically avoided, though nyala, whose males weigh around 120 kg (260 lb), were found to be the major prey in a study in the Phinda Game Reserve.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In Namibia cheetahs are the major predators of livestock.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In Kruger National Park there are exceptional records of two giraffe calves and two cape buffalo calves hunted by cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The diet of the Asiatic cheetah consists of chinkara, desert hare, goitered gazelle, urial, wild goats, and livestock; in India cheetahs used to prey mostly on blackbuck.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Prey preferences and hunting success vary with the age, sex, number of cheetahs involved in the hunt, and the vigilance of the prey.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Generally, only male coalitions or mother with cubs try to kill larger prey; mothers with cubs look out for larger prey more frequently.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Individuals on the periphery of the prey herd are common targets; vigilant prey which react quickly on seeing a cheetah are not preferred.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah is one of the most iconic pursuit predators, hunting primarily throughout the day, sometimes with peaks at dawn and dusk and avoiding larger predators like the mainly nocturnal lion.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs in the Sahara, and Maasai Mara in Kenya, hunt after sunset to escape high temperatures.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs use their vision to hunt; they keep a lookout for prey from resting sites or low branches.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah can close without hiding within 60–70 m (200–230 ft) of the prey, before sprinting for them.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Alternatively the cheetah can stalk in cover and close to within 30m.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A stalking cheetah assumes a partially crouched posture, with the head lower than the shoulders; it moves slowly and remains still at times.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In areas of minimal cover, the cheetah may approach within 200 m (660 ft) of the prey and start the chase.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A cheetah can give up if it is detected early.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In a 2013 study, the length of chases averaged 173 m (568 ft), and the longest run measured 559 m (1,834 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] To strike down its prey, the cheetah use the well developed and sharp dewclaws of their forepaws to hook the limbs or rump of the prey in full pursuit, and thus disrupt its balance and cause it to fall, allowing the cheetah to pounce on it.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Such a fall during a high-speed chase may cause the prey to collapse hard enough to break its limbs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Once the cheetah has overtaken its prey, it follows closely behind as the prey makes 3–4 zigzag twists in an attempt to escape; if the prey has not escaped by then, it is captured.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] To kill large prey, the cheetah squeezes their throats with its jaws, strangling them, and maintains its clamp for 5 minutes, which is when the prey stops struggling.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A bite on the nape of the neck or the skull suffices to kill small prey.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs have a general hunting success rate of 25–40%.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Once the hunt is over, cheetahs drag their kill near a bush or under a tree.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] When there is no cover, they move its kill for an average of 64.5 m (212 ft) from the kill site; one individual dragged a kill for 712 m (2,336 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Like other cats, a cheetah is exhausted after killing their prey and rests beside the kill, panting for 20–30 minutes, while a lion rest for 15–40 minutes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Meanwhile, cheetahs nearby, who did not take part in the hunt, might feed on the kill immediately.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Groups of cheetah consume the kill peacefully, though minor noises and snapping may be observed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs can consume large quantities of food; a cheetah at the Etosha National Park, Namibia, was found to consume as much as 10 kg (22 lb) within two hours.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] However, on a daily basis, a cheetah feeds on around 4 kg (8.8 lb) of meat.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Mothers with cubs remain cautious even as they eat, pausing to look around for predators who may steal the kill.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetahs moves its head from side to side so the blade-like shape carnassial teeth tear the flesh, which it can then swallow without chewing.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] It typically begins with the hindquarters where the tissue is soft, and then progresses toward the abdomen and the spine.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] It chews ribs on at the ends, but does not tear the limbs apart while eating.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Unless the prey is very small, it leaves the skeleton almost intact.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] It loses 9–14% of its kills to larger and stronger predators.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Unlike the African wild dog, the cheetah can cope with a 25% loss of kills, needing to spend only 4 hours per day to hunting to recover the energy wasted; due to its high speed, short duration pursuit strategy, it is energetically flexible.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Males and single females spend more time eating as quickly as possible after kill its prey, while mothers with cubs spend more time watching their surroundings while their cubs eat.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A few cases of cheetahs scavenging carcasses they did not hunt have been observed, including an incident of a mother and her three 15-month cubs stealing a kill of a lone spotted hyena.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah appears to have a higher hunting success rate than other predators; in the Serengeti, its success rate for hunting Thomson gazelles is 70%, whereas for the African wild dog it is 57%, for the spotted hyena 33%, and for the lion 26%.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In the Okavango delta, its success rate for hunting impalas is 26%, but of the African wild dog only 15.5%.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In Kruger National Park, its success rate for hunting impalas is 20.7% whereas that of the leopard is 16%.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah breeds throughout the year; females are polyestrous and induced ovulators with an estrous cycle of 12 days on average that can vary from three days to a month.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] They have their first litter at two to three years of age and can conceive again after 17 to 20 months from giving birth, or even sooner if a whole litter is lost.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Males can breed at less than two years of age in captivity, but this may be delayed in the wild until the male acquires a territory.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A 2007 study showed that females who gave birth to more litters early in their life often died younger, indicating a trade-off between longevity and yearly reproductive success.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Urine-marking in males can become more pronounced when a female in their vicinity comes into estrus.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Males, sometimes even those in coalitions, fight among one another to secure access to the female.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Often one male will eventually win dominance over the others and mate with the female, though a female can mate with different males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Mating begins with the male approaching the female, who lies down on the ground; individuals often chirp, purr or yelp at this time.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] No courtship behaviour is observed; the male immediately secures hold of the female's nape, and copulation takes place.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The pair then ignore each other, but meet and copulate a few more times three to five times a day for the next two to three days before finally parting ways.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] After a gestation of nearly three months, a litter of up six to eight cubs is born.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Though those of three to four cubs are more common.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs' litters tend to be larger than those of most of felid species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Births take place at 20–25 minute intervals in a sheltered place such as thick vegetation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The eyes are shut at birth, and open in four to 11 days.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Newborn cubs might spit a lot and make soft churring noises; they start walking by two weeks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Their nape, shoulders and back are thickly covered with long bluish-grey hair, called a mantle, which gives them a mohawk-type appearance; this fur is shed as the cheetah grows older.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A study suggested that this mane gives a cheetah cub the appearance of a honey badger, and could act as camouflage from attacks by these badgers or predators that tend to avoid them.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Mothers keep their cubs hidden in dense vegetation for the first two months and nurse in the early morning.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The mother is extremely vigilant at this stage; she stays within 1 km (0.62 mi) of the lair, frequently visits her cubs, moves them every five to six days, and remains with them after dark.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Despite trying to make minimal noise, she cannot generally defend her litter from predators.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Predators are the main cause of death for cubs; of the total deaths, 58.3% were due to predators in the Serengeti, and 88.9% were in the Kgalagadi Transfrontier Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Deaths also occur from starvation if their mothers abandon them, fires, or pneumonia because of exposure to bad weather.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Generation length of the cheetah is six years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cubs start coming out of the lair at two months of age, trailing after their mother wherever she goes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] At this point the mother nurses less and brings solid food to the cubs; they retreat away from the carcass in fear initially, but gradually start eating it.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cubs might purr as the mother licks them clean after the meal.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] To train her cubs in hunting, the mother will catch and let go of live prey in front of her cubs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cubs' play behaviour includes chasing, crouching, pouncing and wrestling; there is plenty of agility, and attacks are seldom lethal.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Playing can improve catching skills in cubs, though the ability to crouch and hide may not develop remarkably.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cubs as young as six months try to capture small prey like hares and young gazelles.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] However, they may have to wait until as long as 15 months of age to make a successful kill on their own.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] At around 20 months, offspring become independent; mothers might have conceived again by then.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Siblings may remain together for a few more months before parting ways.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] While females stay close to their mothers, males move farther off.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The lifespan of wild cheetahs is 14 to 15 years for females, and their reproductive cycle typically ends by 12 years of age; males generally live as long as ten years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In the Serengeti, cheetahs lose about 4% of their kills to spotted hyenas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs sometimes attempt to protect their kills from larger carnivores by making threatening vocalizations and lunges, but retreat if it persist.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In Iran, cheetahs compete with leopards for chinkara, bezoar ibex and urial.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In the Bafq Protected Area, cheetahs avoided leopards by moving to lower elevations, though one cheetah was killed by a leopard during the study period.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetah mothers have been observed to drive off leopards threatening their cubs, and large male cheetahs may chase leopards for considerable distances.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In north-central Namibia, 34% of scent marking sites were shared by cheetahs and leopards, though they avoid interacting with each other by marking at different times, with cheetahs visiting such sites at night, while leopards do so in the morning.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Unlike the African wild dog, the cheetah's population density in an area remains stable even when lion population density increases, despite the high risk of juvenile mortality; its mainly solitary nature attracts little attention.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] One case of a black-backed jackal distracting preys so a cheetah can catch it is know.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah is threatened by several factors, like habitat loss and fragmentation of populations.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Habitat loss is caused mainly by the introduction of commercial land use, such as agriculture and industry.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] It is further aggravated by ecological degradation, like woody plant encroachment, which is common in southern Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Moreover, the species apparently requires a sizeable area to live in as indicated by its low population densities.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Shortage of prey and conflict with other species such as humans and large carnivores are other major threats.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah appears to be less capable of coexisting with humans than the leopard.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] With 76% of its range consisting of unprotected land, the cheetah is often targeted by farmers and pastoralists who attempt to protect their livestock, especially in Namibia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Illegal wildlife trade and trafficking is another problem in some places (like Ethiopia).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Some tribes, like the Maasai people in Tanzania, have been reported to use cheetah skins in ceremonies.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Roadkill is a threat in areas where roads have been constructed in natural habitats or through protected areas; roadkilled cheetahs were found in Kalmand, Touran National Park and Bafq in Iran.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The reduced genetic variability makes cheetahs more vulnerable to diseases; however, the threat posed by infectious diseases may be minor, given the low population densities and hence a reduced chance of infection.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah has been classified as Vulnerable on the IUCN Red List; it is listed under Appendix I of the Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals and Appendix I of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The Endangered Species Act enlists the cheetah as Endangered.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Until the 1970s, cheetahs and other carnivores were frequently killed to protect livestock in Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Gradually the understanding of cheetah ecology increased and their falling numbers became a matter of concern.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The De Wildt Cheetah and Wildlife Centre was set up in 1971 in South Africa to provide care for wild cheetahs regularly trapped or injured by Namibian farmers.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] By 1987, the first major research project to outline cheetah conservation strategies was underway.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The Cheetah Conservation Fund, founded in 1990 in Namibia, put efforts into field research and education about cheetahs on the global platform.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] It runs a cheetah genetics laboratory, the only one of its kind, in Otjiwarongo; "Bushblok" is an initiative to restore habitat systematically through targeted bush thinning and biomass utilisation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Several more cheetah-specific conservation programmes have since been established, like Cheetah Outreach in South Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The Global Cheetah Action Plan Workshop in 2002 laid emphasis on the need for a range-wide survey of wild cheetahs to demarcate areas for conservation efforts and on creating awareness through training programs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The Range Wide Conservation Program for Cheetah and African Wild Dogs began in 2007 as a joint initiative of the IUCN Cat and Canid Specialist Groups, the Wildlife Conservation Society and the Zoological Society of London.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] National conservation plans have been developed for several African countries.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In 2014, the CITES Standing Committee recognised the cheetah as a "species of priority" in its strategies in northeastern Africa to counter wildlife trafficking.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah was reintroduced in Malawi in 2017.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In 2001, the Iranian government collaborated with the CCF, the IUCN, Panthera Corporation, United Nations Development Programme and the Wildlife Conservation Society on the Conservation of Asiatic Cheetah Project (CACP) to protect the natural habitat of the Asiatic cheetah and its prey.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In 2004, the Iranian Centre for Sustainable Development (CENESTA) conducted an international workshop to discuss conservation plans with local stakeholders.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Iran declared 31 August as National Cheetah Day in 2006.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The Iranian Cheetah Strategic Planning meet in 2010 formulated a five-year conservation plan for Asiatic cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The CACP Phase II was implemented in 2009, and the third phase was drafted in 2018.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] During the early 2000s scientists from the Centre for Cellular and Molecular Biology (Hyderabad) proposed a plan to clone Asiatic cheetahs from Iran for reintroduction in India, but Iran denied the proposal.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In September 2009, the Minister of Environment and Forests assigned the Wildlife Trust of India and the Wildlife Institute of India with examining the potential of importing African cheetahs to India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Kuno Wildlife Sanctuary and Nauradehi Wildlife Sanctuary were suggested as reintroduction sites for the cheetah because of the high prey density.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] However, plans for reintroduction were stalled in May 2012 by the Supreme Court of India because of a political dispute and concerns over introducing a non-native species to the country.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Opponents stated the plan was "not a case of intentional movement of an organism into a part of its native range".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] On 28 January 2020, the Supreme Court allowed the central government to introduce cheetahs to a suitable habitat in India on an experimental basis to see if they can adapt to it.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In 2020, India signed a memorandum of understanding with Namibia as part of Project Cheetah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In July 2022, it was announced that eight cheetahs would be transferred from Namibia to India in August.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The eight cheetahs were released into Kuno National Park on 17 September 2022.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Since their introduction, they gave birth to 17 cubs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] However, by September 2024, eight adult cheetahs and four cubs already died.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah has been tamed easily since antiquity by the nobility.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The earliest known depictions of the cheetah are from the Chauvet Cave in France, dating back to 32,000–26,000 BC.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] According to historians such as Heinz Friederichs and Burchard Brentjes, the cheetah was first tamed in Sumer and this gradually spread out to central and northern Africa, from where it reached India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The evidence for this is mainly pictorial; for instance, a Sumerian seal dating back to c.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] 3000 BC, featuring a long-legged leashed animal has fueled speculation that the cheetah was first tamed in Sumer.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] However, Thomas Allsen argues that the depicted animal might be a large dog.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Other historians, such as Frederick Zeuner, have opined that ancient Egyptians were the first to tame the cheetah, from where it gradually spread into central Asia, Iran and India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In comparison, theories of the cheetah's taming in Egypt are stronger and include timelines proposed on this basis.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Mafdet, one of the ancient Egyptian deities worshiped during the First Dynasty (3100–2900 BC), was sometimes depicted as a cheetah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Ancient Egyptians believed the spirits of deceased pharaohs were taken away by cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Reliefs in the Deir el-Bahari temple complex tell of an expedition by Egyptians to the Land of Punt during the reign of Hatshepsut (1507–1458 BC) that fetched, among other things, animals called "panthers".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] During the New Kingdom (16th to 11th centuries BC), cheetahs were common pets for royalty, who adorned them with ornate collars and leashes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Rock carvings depicting cheetahs dating back to 2000–6000 years ago have been found in Twyfelfontein; little else has been discovered in connection to the taming of cheetahs (or other cats) in southern Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Hunting cheetahs are known in pre-Islamic Arabic art from Yemen.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Hunting with cheetahs became more prevalent toward the seventh century AD.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In the Middle East, the cheetah would accompany the nobility to hunts in a special seat on the back of the saddle.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Taming was an elaborate process and could take a year to complete.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The Romans may have referred to the cheetah as the *leopardos* (λεοπάρδος) or *leontopardos* (λεοντόπαρδος), believing it to be a hybrid between a leopard and a lion because of the mantle seen in cheetah cubs and the difficulty of breeding them in captivity.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] A Roman hunting cheetah is depicted in a 4th-century mosaic from Lod, Israel.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Cheetahs continued to be used into the Byzantine period of the Roman Empire, with "hunting leopards" being mentioned in the *Cynegetica* (283/284 AD).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In eastern Asia, records are confusing as regional names for the leopard and the cheetah may be used interchangeably.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The earliest depiction of cheetahs from eastern Asia dates back to the Tang dynasty (7th to 10th centuries AD); paintings depict tethered cheetahs and cheetahs mounted on horses.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Chinese emperors would use cheetahs and caracals as gifts.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In the 13th and 14th centuries, the Yuan rulers bought numerous cheetahs from the western parts of the empire and from Muslim merchants.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] According to the *Ming Shilu*, the subsequent Ming dynasty (14th to 17th centuries) continued this practice.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Tomb figurines from the Mongol empire, dating back to the reign of Kublai Khan (1260–1294 AD), represent cheetahs on horseback.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The Mughal ruler Akbar the Great (1556–1605 AD) is said to have kept as many as 1000 *khasa* (imperial) cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] His son Jahangir wrote in his memoirs, *Tuzk-e-Jahangiri*, that only one of them gave birth.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Mughal rulers trained cheetahs and caracals in a similar way as the western Asians, and used them to hunt game, especially blackbuck.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The rampant hunting severely affected the populations of wild animals in India; by 1927, cheetahs had to be imported from Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The first cheetah to be brought into captivity in a zoo was at the Zoological Society of London in 1829.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Early captive cheetahs showed a high mortality rate, with an average lifespan of 3–4 years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] After trade of wild cheetahs was delimited by the enforcement of CITES in 1975, more efforts were put into breeding in captivity; in 2014 the number of captive cheetahs worldwide was estimated at 1730 individuals, with 87% born in captivity.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Mortality under captivity is generally high; in 2014, 23% of the captive cheetahs worldwide died under one year of age, mostly within a month of birth.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Although a comparative study from 1985 found that cheetah cub mortality at 24% was generally lower than the average of 33% for 17 carnivore mammals, including 9 felids; cheetah cub mortality was the second lowest among felids.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Deaths result from several reasons—stillbirths, birth defects, maternal neglect, and diseases.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Compared to other felids, cheetahs need specialised care because of their higher vulnerability to stress-induced diseases; this has been attributed to their low genetic variability and factors of captive life.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Common diseases of cheetahs include feline herpesvirus, feline infectious peritonitis, gastroenteritis, glomerulosclerosis, leukoencephalopathy, myelopathy, nephrosclerosis and veno-occlusive disease.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] High density of cheetahs in a place, closeness to other large carnivores in enclosures, improper handling, exposure to public and frequent movement between zoos can be sources of stress for cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Recommended management practices for cheetahs include spacious and ample access to outdoors, stress minimisation by exercise and limited handling, and following proper hand-rearing protocols (especially for pregnant females).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Wild cheetahs are far more successful breeders than captive cheetahs; this has also been linked to increased stress levels in captive individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In a study in the Serengeti, females were found to have a 95% success rate in breeding, compared to 20% recorded for North American captive cheetahs in another study.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In November 2017, a cheetah gave birth to eight cubs at the Saint Louis Zoo, setting a record for the most births recorded by the Association of Zoos and Aquariums.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Chances of successful mating in captive males can be improved by replicating social groups such as coalitions observed in the wild.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] There are no documented records of lethal attacks on humans by wild cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] However, there have been instances of people being fatally mauled by captive cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In 2007, a 37-year-old woman from Antwerp was killed by a cheetah in a Belgian zoo after sneaking into its cage outside of visiting hours.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In 2017, a three-year-old child was attacked by a captive cheetah on a farm in Philippolis, South Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] Despite being airlifted to a hospital in Bloemfontein, the boy died from his injuries.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetah has been widely portrayed in a variety of artistic works.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In *Bacchus and Ariadne*, an oil painting by the 16th-century Italian painter Titian, the chariot of the Greek god Dionysus (Bacchus) is depicted as being drawn by two cheetahs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The cheetahs in the painting were previously considered to be leopards.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] In 1764, English painter George Stubbs commemorated the gifting of a cheetah to King George III by the English Governor of Madras, Sir George Pigot in his painting *Cheetah with Two Indian Attendants and a Stag*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The painting depicts a cheetah, hooded and collared by two Indian servants, along with a stag it was supposed to prey upon.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] The 1896 painting *The Caress* by the 19th-century Belgian symbolist painter Fernand Khnopff is a representation of the myth of Oedipus and the Sphinx and portrays a creature with a woman's head and a cheetah's body.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/acinonyx-jubatus-p02] According to theologian Philip Schaff, the "leopard" mentioned in Habakkuk 1:8 could actually be a cheetah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The **Asian small-clawed otter** (***Aonyx cinereus***), also called **oriental small-clawed otter** and **small-clawed otter**, is an otter species native to South and Southeast Asia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It has short claws that do not extend beyond the pads of its webbed digits.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] With a total body length of 730 to 960 mm (28.6 to 37.6 in), and a maximum weight of 3.5 kg (7.7 lb), it is the smallest otter species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter lives in riverine habitats, freshwater wetlands and mangrove swamps.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It feeds on molluscs, crabs and other small aquatic animals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It lives in pairs, but also has been observed in family groups with up to 12 individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It is listed as Vulnerable on the IUCN Red List, and is threatened by habitat loss, pollution, and in some areas also by hunting.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Results of a mitochondrial cytochrome B analysis published in 1998 indicated that it should be subordinated to the genus *Aonyx*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Results of a molecular study published in 2008 showed that the Asian small-clawed otter is a sister taxon of *Lutrogale*, lending support to retaining the genus *Amblonyx* or expanding *Aonyx* to make it monophyletic.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] They genetically diverged about 1.5 million years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter groups with the African clawless otter (*Aonyx capensis*) and the smooth-coated otter (*Lutrogale perspicillata*) into a sister clade with the genus *Lutra*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Hybridisation of Asian small-clawed otter females with smooth-coated otter males occurred in Singapore.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The resulting offspring and their descendants bred back into the smooth-coated otter population, but maintained the genes of their small-clawed otter ancestors; a population of at least 60 hybrid otters are present in Singapore as of 2016.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter has deep brown fur with some rufous tinge on the back, but paler below.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The sides of the neck and head are brown, but its cheeks, upperlip, chin, throat and sides of the neck are whitish.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Its skull is short, and the naked rhinarium rounded above.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The muzzle has long coarse vibrissae on either side.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Its eyes are located toward the front of the head.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The small ears are oval-shaped with an inconspicuous tragus and antitragus.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Its paws are narrow with short digits that are webbed to the last joint.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] There are short hairs on the lower sides of the interdigital webs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The four-lobed plantar pads are longer than wide.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The claws are short, almost erect, and in some individuals even absent.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter is the smallest otter species in Asia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The tapering tail is thick and muscular, especially at the base, and more than half the length of the body.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Hind feet are 97 to 102 mm (3.8 to 4 in) long.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Length of skull ranges from 3.3 to 3.7 in (84 to 94 mm).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It does not have upper premolars and only four cheek teeth above.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Adult captive otters range in weight from 2.7 to 3.5 kg (6.0 to 7.7 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter's native range comprises parts of India to Southeast Asia including the islands of Sumatra, Java, Borneo and Palawan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It lives in freshwater wetlands such as swamps, meandering rivers, irrigated rice fields as well as estuaries, coastal lagoons and tidal pools.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It occurs in West Bengal, Assam and Arunachal Pradesh, and in coastal regions of Odisha.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] In Karnataka, Nilgiri and Palni hills in Tamil Nadu, it lives in shallow mountain creeks up to an elevation of 2,000 m (6,600 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] In West Java, it inhabits areas along slow-flowing irrigation channels, pond areas and rice fields surrounded by vegetation that offers shelter.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] In February 2025, the Asian small-clawed otter was photographed in Dadeldhura District in far-western Nepal.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] In the 1980s, a few Asian small-clawed otters escaped from captivity in England and established a population in the wild.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It was likely driven out by the recovery of the native Eurasian otter.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter is mostly active after dark.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It lives in groups of up to 15 individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] In the Bangladesh Sundarbans, 53 individuals were recorded in 351 km (218 mi) of water courses in 13 locations between November 2014 and March 2015.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Group size ranged from one to 12 individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Group members communicate using 12 or more distinct calls, and utter a variety of yelps and whimpers.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] When disturbed, they scream to rally the help of others.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] When swimming on the surface, otters row with the forelimbs and paddle with the hind limbs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] When diving under water, they undulate their bodies and tails.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Observations of wild Asian small-clawed otters revealed that they smear their spraint at latrine sites, using their hind feet and tails.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Large groups smeared more than groups of three or fewer animals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The frequency of latrines with smeared scats varied in different locations, indicating a preference for certain sites.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Spraint smearing most likely facilitates social ties among group members and is associated with territorial marking displays.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] They use grassy or sandy banks for resting, sun bathing and grooming.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter feeds mainly on crabs, mudskippers and *Trichogaster* fish.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] When and where available, it also catches snakes, frogs, insects, rats and ricefield fish like catfish, *Anabas testudineus* and *Channa striata*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The size of crabs found in spraints in Huai Kha Khaeng Wildlife Sanctuary ranged in carapace width from 10 to 44 cm (3.9 to 17.3 in).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Captive Asian small-clawed otters were observed to leave shellfish in the sun so the heat causes them to open, making it possible for them to eat them without having to crush the shells.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Information about the Asian small-clawed otter's mating and breeding behaviour has been studied in captive environments.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The estrous cycle of females lasts 28 to 30 days with estrus lasting between one and 13 days.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Usually, mating takes place in the water.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Interval between births is at least eight months.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] About two weeks before parturition, both female and male engage in building a nest.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] They collect grass, hay or straw and carry this material into the breeding chamber.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Between one and seven pups are born in a litter.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Pups are born with closed eyes, which open in the fifth week.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] They start exploring the environs of the breeding den at the age of ten weeks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] At about three months, they enter and paddle in shallow water under the guidance of the mother.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] They become independent at the age of four to five months.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter is threatened by poaching for its fur, loss and destruction of habitats such as hill streams, peat swamp forests and mangroves for aquaculture projects.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Threats in India include deforestation, conversion of natural habitat for tea and coffee plantations, overfishing of rivers and water pollution through pesticides.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] It is the most sought after otter species for the illegal pet trade in Asia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] At least 711 Asian small-clawed otters were offered for sale through online websites by 280 traders in Indonesia, Thailand, Malaysia and Vietnam between 2016 and 2017.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Between December 2015 and October 2018, 49 Asian small-clawed otters were confiscated from wildlife traffickers in Thailand, Vietnam and Japan; 35 of them were bound for sale in Japan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Asian small-clawed otter was listed on CITES Appendix II and is protected in almost all range countries prohibiting its killing.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Since August 2019, it is included in CITES Appendix I, thus strengthening its protection in regards to international trade.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] The Association of Zoos and Aquariums established a Species Survival Plan for the Asian small-clawed otter in 1983 to encourage research on captive breeding.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] In Europe, Zoo Basel keeps Asian small-clawed otters together with Indian rhinoceros.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] In Tallinn Zoo, Asian small-clawed otters share an enclosure with a binturong.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asian-short-clawed-otter] Asian small-clawed otters with osteoporosis display resorption of hyperactive bone and cartilage by osteoclasts in many bone sites, which causes pockmarks on all the bones.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The **Asian black bear** (***Ursus thibetanus***), also known as the **Asiatic black bear**, **moon bear** and **white-chested bear**, is a medium-sized bear species native to Asia that is largely adapted to an arboreal lifestyle.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is distributed from southeastern Iran, Pakistan, India and the Himalayas to mainland Southeast Asia, the Korean Peninsula, Taiwan, mainland China and the Russian Far East to the islands of Honshū and Shikoku in Japan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is listed as vulnerable on the IUCN Red List, and is threatened by deforestation and poaching for its body parts, which are used in traditional medicine.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Biologically and morphologically, the Asian black bear represents the beginning of the arboreal specializations attained by sloth bears and sun bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It has karyotypes nearly identical to those of the five other ursine bears, and has 74 chromosomes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is considered the least derived of the Old World bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is either a surviving, albeit modified, form of *Ursus etruscus*, specifically the early, small variety of the Middle Villafranchian or a larger form of *Ursus minimus*, an extinct species that arose 4 million years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] With the exception of the age of the bones, it is often difficult to distinguish the remains of *Ursus minimus* with those of the modern Asian black bear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear and the American black bear are thought to have genetically diverged 3 million years ago, though genetic evidence is inconclusive.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Both the American and Asian black species are considered sister taxa and are more closely related to each other than to the other bear species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The earliest known Asian black bear specimens are known from the early Pliocene in Moldova.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The earliest American black bear fossils found in Pennsylvania greatly resemble the Asian black bear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Until the Late Pleistocene, two further subspecies ranged across Europe and West Asia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] These are *U. t. mediterraneus* from Western Europe and the Caucasus and *U. t. permjak* from Eastern Europe, particularly the Ural Mountains.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are reproductively compatible with several other bear species, and have on occasion produced hybrid offspring.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 1975, within Venezuela's "Las Delicias" Zoo, a female Asian black bear shared her enclosure with a male spectacled bear, and produced several hybrid descendants.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2005, a possible Asian black bear–sun bear hybrid cub was captured in the Mekong River watershed of eastern Cambodia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] An Asian black bear/brown bear hybrid, taken from a bile farm, is housed at the Animals Asia Foundation's China Moon Bear Rescue as of 2010.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear has black fur, a light brown muzzle, and a distinct whitish or creamy patch on the chest, which is sometimes V-shaped.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Its ears are bell shaped, proportionately longer than those of other bears, and stick out sideways from the head.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Its tail is short, around 11 cm (4.3 in) long.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Adult males weigh 60–200 kg (130–440 lb) with an average weight of about 135 kg (298 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear is similar in general build to the brown bear (*Ursus arctos*), but is lighter and smaller.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The lips and nose are larger and more mobile than those of brown bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The skull of the Asian black bear is relatively small but massive, particularly in the lower jaw.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although the Asian black bear is mostly herbivorous, its jaw structure is not as specialized for plant eating as that of the giant panda; Asian black bears have much narrower zygomatic arches, and the weight ratio of the two pterygoid muscles is also much smaller in Asian black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The lateral slips of the temporal muscles are thicker and stronger in Asian black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In contrast to the polar bear, the Asian black bear has a powerful upper body for climbing trees, and relatively weak hind legs which are shorter than those in the brown bear and American black bear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] An Asian black bear with broken hind legs can still climb effectively.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It is the most bipedal of all bears, and can walk upright for over 400 m (0.25 mi).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The heel pads on the forefeet are larger than those of most other bear species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Their claws, which are primarily used for climbing and digging, are slightly longer on the fore foot at 30–45 mm (1.2–1.8 in) than the back foot at 18–36 mm (0.71–1.42 in), and are larger and more hooked than those of the American black bear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] On average, adult Asian black bears are slightly smaller than American black bears, though large males can exceed the size of several other bear species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The famed British sportsman known as the "Old Shekarry" wrote of how an Asian black bear he shot in India probably weighed no less than 363 kg (800 lb) based on how many people it took to lift its body.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The largest Asian black bear on record allegedly weighed 200 kg (440 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Zoo-kept specimens can weigh up to 225 kg (496 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although their senses are more acute than those of brown bears, their eyesight is poor, and their hearing range is moderate, the upper limit being 30 kHz.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] During the Middle Pleistocene and early Late Pleistocene, the Asian black bear ranged from the Iberian Peninsula, the Balkans to the Ural Mountains.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Today, it occurs very patchily in its former range from southeastern Iran eastward through Afghanistan and Pakistan, across the foothills of the Himalayas in India and Myanmar to mainland Southeast Asia, except Malaysia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Its range in mainland China is patchy in the northeast and south, Hainan, and it is absent in much of east-central China.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Other population clusters exist in Taiwan, the southern Russian Far East and in North Korea.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Small remnant populations survive in South Korea, and on Honshu and Shikoku islands.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It typically inhabits deciduous forests, mixed forests and thornbrush forests.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In the summer, it usually inhabits elevations of around 3,500 m (11,480 ft) in the Himalayas but rarely above 3,700 m (12,000 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In winter, it descends to elevations below 1,500 m (4,920 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There is no definitive estimate as to the number of Asian black bears: Japan posed estimates of 8–14,000 bears living on Honshū, though the reliability of this is now doubted.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although their reliability is unclear, rangewide estimates of 5–6,000 Asian black bears have been presented by Russian biologists.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] According to the Mammal Society of Japan, the introduction of conservation policies by the Ministry of the Environment, along with a decline in hunters due to an aging population, has led to a significant increase in the population and expansion of the range of the Japanese black bear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Estimates indicate that the population rose from approximately 15,000 individuals in 2012 to around 44,000 in 2023.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Rough density estimates without corroborating methodology or data have been made in India and Pakistan, resulting in the estimates of 7–9,000 in India and 1,000 in Pakistan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Unsubstantiated estimates from China give varying estimates between 15 and 46,000, with a government estimate of 28,000.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Wildlife Trust of Bangladesh conducted an on-field survey of bears in Bangladesh from 2008 to 2010 that included Asian black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The survey was done in 87 different places, mostly in the north-central, northeastern and southeastern areas of Bangladesh that had historical presence of bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The survey result says that most of the areas still has some isolated small bear populations, mainly the Asian black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] According to the survey, the most evidence found relating to bears were of Asian black bears that included nests, footprints, local sightings, etc.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There are many reports on the presence of Asian black bears in the central, north-central, northeastern and southeastern parts of Bangladesh.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although Asian black bears still occur in different parts of Bangladesh, mainly in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, the population is very small.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Conservationists fear that the species will soon be extinct in the country if necessary steps to protect it are not taken in the near future.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Three subspecies of the Asian black bear occur in China: the Tibetan subspecies (*U. thibetanus thibetanus*), the Indochinese subspecies (*U. thibetanus mupinensis*), and the northeastern subspecies (*U. thibetanus ussuricus*), which is the only subspecies of bear in northeastern China.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are mainly distributed in the conifer forests in the cold and temperate zones of northeast China, the main areas being Changbai, Zhang Guangcai, Lao Ye, and the Lesser Xingan Mountains.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within Liaoning province, there are about 100 Asian black bears, which only inhabit the five counties of Xinbin, Huanren, Benxi, Kuandian, and Fencheng.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within Jilin province, Asian black bears occur mainly in the counties of Hunchun, Dunhua, Wangqing, Antu, Changbai, Fusong, Jiaohe, Huadian, Panshi, and Shulan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Heilongjiang province, Asian black bears occur in the counties of Ningan, Bayan, Wuchang, Tonghe, Baoqing, Fuyuan, Yichun, Taoshan, Lanxi, Tieli, Sunwu, Aihui, Dedu, Beian, and Nenjiang.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] This population has a northern boundary of about 50° N and the southern boundary in Fengcheng is about 40°30" N.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By the 1990s, poaching, habitat destruction, and eradication during the Japanese occupation had led to the local extinction of the species from South Korea.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2004, the South Korean government initiated a reintroduction program in Jiri Mountain National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The effort has been successful, with bears now inhabiting the park and dispersing into northern forests.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2021, the park's bear population appeared to have reached its carrying capacity.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Korea, most of the Asian black bears live in the broad-leaved forest of the alpine region, more than 1,500 meters north of Jirisan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As of April 2018, there were 56 bears living in the wild of Jirisan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, since then, many of these areas have not been revisited to confirm its presence, particularly in the southern districts of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Balochistan and Sindh.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Baluchistan black bear occurs throughout the mountainous Balochistan region in western Pakistan, south-eastern Iran and south-western Afghanistan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Baluchistan black bear is now limited in southwestern Pakistan and southeast Iran.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Siberia, the Asian black bear's northern range runs from Innokenti Bay on the coast of the Sea of Japan southwest to the elevated areas of Sikhote Alin crossing it at the sources of the Samarga River.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] At this point, the boundary directs itself to the north, through the middle course of the Khor, Anyui and Khungari rivers, and comes to the shore of the Amur, crossing it at the level of the mouth of the Gorin River.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Along the Amur river, the species' presence has been noted as far as 51° N.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From there, the territorial boundary runs southwest of the river's left bank, passing through the northern part of Lake Bolon and the juncture point of the Kur and Tunguska.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are encountered in the Urmi's lower course.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within the Ussuri krai, the species is restricted to broad-leaved Manchurian-type forests.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Taiwan, the endemic subspecies of Asian black bear, the Formosan black bear (*Ursus thibetanus formosanus*), is confined to the mountain ranges in the central regions of the island.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It lives along the Central and Snow Mountain Range, with populations in the latter being more common.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The largest population seems to live in Lala mountain in Chatienshan Reserve, the (Snow) Mountain area in Shei-Pa National Park and Taroko National Park south to Tawushan Reserve through Yushan National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] This population is estimated to comprise 200 to 600 individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are diurnal, though they become nocturnal near human habitations.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They will walk in a procession of largest to smallest.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They are good climbers of rocks and trees, and will climb to feed, rest, sun, elude enemies and hibernate.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Some older bears may become too heavy to climb.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Half of their life is spent in trees and they are one of the largest arboreal mammals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In the Ussuri territory in the Russian Far East, Asian black bears can spend up to 15% of their time in trees.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears break branches and twigs to place under themselves when feeding on trees, thus causing many trees in their home ranges to have nest-like structures on their tops.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears will rest for short periods in nests on trees standing fifteen feet or higher.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears do not hibernate over most of their range.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They may hibernate in their colder, northern ranges, though some bears will simply move to lower elevations.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears prepare their dens for hibernation in mid-October, and will sleep from November until March.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Their dens can either be dug-out hollow trees (60 feet above ground), caves or holes in the ground, hollow logs, or steep, mountainous and sunny slopes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They may also den in abandoned brown bear dens.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears tend to den at lower elevations and on less steep slopes than brown bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Female Asian black bears emerge from dens later than do males, and female Asian black bears with cubs emerge later than barren females.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears tend to be less mobile than brown bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] With sufficient food, Asian black bears can remain in an area of roughly 1–2 km2 (0.39–0.77 sq mi), and sometimes even as little as 0.5–1 km2 (0.19–0.39 sq mi).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears have a wide range of vocalizations, including grunts, whines, roars, slurping sounds (sometimes made when feeding) and "an appalling row" when wounded, alarmed or angry.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They emit loud hisses when issuing warnings or threats, and scream when fighting.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] When approaching other bears, they produce "tut tut" sounds, thought to be produced by bears snapping their tongue against the roof of their mouth.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] When courting, they emit clucking sounds.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Within Sikhote-Alin, the breeding season of Asian black bears occurs earlier than in brown bears, starting from mid-June to mid-August.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Birth also occurs earlier, in mid-January.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By October, the uterine horns of pregnant females grow to 15–22 mm (0.59–0.87 in).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By late December, the embryos weigh 75 grams.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Sows generally have their first litter at the age of three years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Pregnant females generally make up 14% of populations.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Similar to brown bears, Asian black bears have delayed implantation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Sows usually give birth in caves or hollow trees in winter or early spring after a gestation period of 200–240 days.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Cubs weigh 13 ounces at birth, and will begin walking at four days of age, and open their eyes three days later.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The skulls of newborn Asian black bear cubs bear great resemblance to those of adult sun bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Litters can consist of 1–4 cubs, with 2 being the average.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Cubs have a slow growth rate, reaching only 2.5 kg by May.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bear cubs will nurse for 104–130 weeks, and become independent at 24–36 months.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There is usually a 2–3 year interval period before females produce subsequent litters.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The average lifespan in the wild is 25 years, while the oldest Asian black bear in captivity died at the age of 44.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear is omnivorous and feeds on insects, beetle larvae, invertebrates, termites, grubs, carrion, bees, eggs, garbage, mushrooms, grasses, bark, roots, tubers, fruits, nuts, seeds, honey, herbs, acorns, cherries, dogwood and grain.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It eats pine nuts and acorns of the previous year in the April–May period.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In times of scarcity, it enters river valleys to gain access to hazelnuts and insect larvae in rotting logs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From mid-May through late June, it supplement its diet with green vegetation and fruit.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Through July to September, it climbs trees to eat bird cherries, pine cones, vines and grapes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] On rare occasions, it eats dead fish during the spawning season, though this constitutes a much lesser portion of its diet.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In the 1970s, Asian black bears were reported to kill and eat Hanuman langurs in Nepal.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It also kills ungulates with some regularity, including domestic livestock.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Wild ungulate prey can include muntjacs, serow, takin, Malayan tapir wild boar and adult water buffaloes, which it kills by breaking their necks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Black bears in Japan, specifically, are reported as mainly eating acorns throughout the year and having similar caloric fluctuations.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Their energy balance declines from May to June, rises again in August through October, and declines once more in November.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Male and female bears both have a higher energy balance in good mast years rather than poor mast years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Moreover, during a poor mast year, male bears' energy intake will become negative in February during their hibernation period, and will not exceed zero until August, even if they can begin feeding earlier in the year.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear's range overlaps with that of the sloth bear in central and southern India, the sun bear in Southeast Asia and the brown bear in the southern part of the Russian Far East.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears seem to intimidate Himalayan brown bears in direct encounters.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] They eat the fruit dropped by Asian black bears from trees, as they themselves are too large and cumbersome to climb.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Ussuri brown bears may attack Asian black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are occasionally attacked by tigers and brown bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Leopards are known to prey on bear cubs younger than two years old.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Packs of wolves and Eurasian lynxes are potential predators of bear cubs as well.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears usually dominate Amur leopards in physical confrontations in heavily vegetated areas, while leopards are uppermost in open areas, though the outcome of such encounters is largely dependent on the size of the individual animals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Tigers occasionally attack and consume Asian black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Russian hunters found their remains in tiger scats, and Asian black bear carcasses showing evidence of tiger predation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] To escape tigers, Asian black bears rush up a tree and wait for the tiger to leave, though some tigers will pretend to leave, and wait for the bear to descend.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Some are very tenacious when attacked: Jim Corbett observed a fight between a tiger and the largest Asian black bear he had ever seen.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The bear managed to chase off the tiger, despite having half its nose and scalp torn off.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] He twice saw Asian black bears carry off tiger kills when the latter was absent.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears are usually safe from tiger attacks once they reach five years of age.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] One fatal attack of a tiger on a juvenile Asian black bear has been recorded in Jigme Dorji National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] One Siberian tiger was reported to have lured an Asian black bear by imitating its mating call.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, Asian black bears are probably less vulnerable to tiger attacks than brown bears, due to their habit of living in hollows or in close set rocks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asian black bear is listed as a protected animal in China's National Protection Wildlife Law, which stipulates that anyone hunting or catching bears without permits will be subject to severe punishment.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Moreover, due to India's wide-stretching boundaries with other nations such as Pakistan, Tibet, China, Nepal, Bhutan, Bangladesh and Myanmar, it is difficult to police such borders, which are often in mountainous terrain.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Five Asian black bear populations, occurring in Kyushu, Shikoku, West-Chugoku, East-Chugoku and Kii areas, were listed as endangered by the Environmental Agency in the Japanese Red Data Book in 1991.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Small isolated populations in the Tanzawa and Shimokita areas of mainland Honshū were listed as endangered in 1995.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2000, the Ministry of the Environment introduced a bear management manual that set an upper limit on the annual capture rate relative to the estimated population, marking a full shift toward conservation policy.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The manual has since undergone several revisions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As hunting quotas declined and as the number of hunters decreased due to an aging population, the Japanese black bear population grew rapidly through 2023, particularly on Honshu.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears occur as an infrequent species in the Red Data Book of Russia, thus falling under special protection and hunting is prohibited.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] There is currently a strong movement to legalize the hunting of Russian black bears, which is supported by most of the local scientific community.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As of January 30, 1989, Taiwan's Formosan black bears have been listed as an endangered species under the Natural and Cultural Heritage Act on, and was later listed as a Conserved Species Category I.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Vietnamese government issued Decision 276/QD, 276/1989, which prohibits the hunting and exporting of Asian black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Red Book of Vietnam lists Vietnamese black bears as endangered.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Korean Government designated the Asian black bear as Natural Monument No.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] 329 and it is considered an extinction crisis.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] At the present time, the Endangered Species Restoration Center of Korea National Park Service is going through species restoration business.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The Asiatic black bear and the subspecies Baluchistan black bear have been classified as vulnerable since 1979 and critically endangered since 1996 in Pakistan, respectively, on the IUCN Red List.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Additionally, they are both listed in Appendix I of the Convention on the International Trade of Endangered Species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The main habitat threat to Asian black bears is overcutting of forests, mainly due to human populations increasing to over 430,000 in regions where bears are distributed, in the Shaanxi, Ganshu, and Sichuan provinces.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] 27 forestry enterprises were built in these areas between 1950 and 1985 (excluding the lumbering units belonging to the county).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] By the early 1990s, the Asian black bear distribution area was reduced to only one-fifth of the area that existed before the 1940s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Isolated bear populations face environmental and genetic stress in these circumstances.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, one of the most important reasons for their decrease involves overhunting, as Asian black bear paws, gall bladders and cubs have great economic value.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bear harvests are maintained at a high level due to the harm they cause to crops, orchards and bee farms.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, 1,000 Asian black bears were harvested annually in the Heilongjiang Province.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] However, purchased furs were reduced by 4/5, even by 9/10 yearly in the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Asian black bears have also been declining annually in Dehong Dai and Jingpo Autonomous Prefecture and Yunnan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Poaching for gall bladders and skin are the main threats faced by Asian black bears in India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Pakistan, in addition to direct killing, commercial poaching, and human-bear conflict, the primary concerns are habitat loss brought on by logging, the growth of plantations and agriculture, road networks, and dams.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From 11,807 km² in the 1950s to 7,925 km² in 2014, the Asiatic black bear population has decreased.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] It primarily inhabits lower-altitude areas of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Gilgit-Baltistan, and Azad Jammu and Kashmir, which are distinguished by densely populated areas, forested vegetation, and related agriculture.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] From the 1970s to the 1980s, Japan conducted large-scale culling of black bears in spring to prevent bark stripping of cedar and cypress plantations, which led to a sharp decline in their population.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In response, from the late 1980s, hunting restrictions and voluntary self-restraint were introduced in western Japan, reducing the number of bears hunted, although poaching remained a problem.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In 2000, the Ministry of the Environment established a management manual aimed at population recovery, explicitly setting annual culling limits based on estimated population size; this manual was subsequently revised several times.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Following this, hunting numbers declined due to both conservation policies and the aging hunter population, allowing the bear population to recover.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Combined with poor mast production caused by climate change, this population recovery contributed to a sharp increase in injuries and fatalities caused by bears around 2023, reaching a record high in 2025.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Consequently, in 2024, the Japanese government revised the existing black bear conservation plan, shifting toward a more proactive population management policy through hunting, with many bears again becoming targets for culling.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Although Asian black bears have been afforded protection in Russia since 1983, illegal poaching, fueled by a growing demand for bear parts in the Asian market, is still a major threat to the Russian population.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Many workers of Chinese and Korean origin, supposedly employed in the timber industry, are actually involved in the illegal trade.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Some Russian sailors reportedly purchase bear parts from local hunters to sell them to Japanese and Southeast Asian clients.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Russia's rapidly growing timber industry has been a serious threat to the Asian black bear's home range for three decades.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The cutting of trees containing cavities deprives Asian black bears of their main source of dens, and forces them to den on the ground or in rocks, thus making them more vulnerable to tigers, brown bears and hunters.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In Taiwan, Asian black bears are not actively pursued, though steel traps set out for wild boars have been responsible for unintentional bear trappings.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] The building of new cross island highways through bear habitat is also potentially threatening.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Vietnamese black bear populations have declined rapidly due to the pressures of human population growth and unstable settlement.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Vietnamese forests have been shrinking: of the 87,000 km2 (34,000 sq mi) of natural forests, about 1,000 km2 (390 sq mi) disappear every year.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Hunting pressures have also increased with a coinciding decline of environmental awareness.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] South Korea remains one of two countries to allow bear bile farming to continue legally.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As reported in 2009, approximately 1,374 Asian black bears reside in an estimated 74 bear farms, where they are kept for slaughter to fuel the demands of traditional Asian medicine.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In sharp contrast, fewer than 20 Asian black bears can be found at Jirisan Restoration Center, located in Korea's Jirisan National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] In recent years, climate change has also contributed to the declining Asian black bear population across southern and southeastern Iran.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] As large mammals, these bears respond more to climate change than small prey species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Due to their large size, Asian black bears are unable to utilize micro-climatic refuges, like hiding in grass to regulate temperature.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Over the past thirty years, a thirty to forty percent decrease has been reported in the Asian black bear population, correlating with the rise in global temperatures.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p01] Along with that, a ten percent decrease in suitable habitat has been reported since 2016, due to climate change and deforestation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Japanese culture, the Asian black bear is traditionally associated with the mountain spirit (*yama no kami*) and is characterized variously as 'mountain man' (**yamaotoko**), 'mountain uncle' (*yama no ossan*), 'mountain father' (*yama no oyaji*), a loving mother, and a child.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Being a largely solitary creature, the Asian black bear is also viewed as 'lonely person' (*sabishigariya*).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears feature very little in lowland Japanese folklore, but are prominent in upland Japan, a fact thought to reflect the bear's greater economic value in upland areas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] According to the local folklore in Kituarahara-gun in Niigata, the Asian black bear received its white mark after being given a silk-wrapped amulet by *yama no kami*, which left the mark after being removed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Hindu mythology, the Asian black bear Jambavantha (also known as Jambavan or Jamvanta) is believed to have lived from Treta Yuga to Dvapara Yuga.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the epic *Ramayana*, Jambavantha assists Rama in finding his wife Sita and battle her abductor, Ravana.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Asian black bear in Thailand is called *mi khwai* (Thai: หมีควาย), meaning 'buffalo bear', not due to its appearance, but a v-shaped patch of fur under its neck similar to that of a buffalo.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] There is also a Thai idiom, *bon meuan mi kin pheung* (Thai: บ่นเหมือนหมีกินผึ้ง), literally 'grumbling like a bear eating honey', referring to people who display behaviors of grumbling and mumbling to express dissatisfaction.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] This idiom comes from the behavior of this species of bear when it climbs trees in search of honey and young bees.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] While eating honey, it makes a murmuring sound.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Taiwan, the Bunun people regard bears and humans as sharing common ancestry.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Formosan black bear emerged as a symbol of Taiwanese nationalism in the 21st century, often in contradistinction or shown in conflict with the panda (as a symbol of the PRC), or with Winnie-the-Pooh (as a symbol of Xi Jinping).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears are briefly mentioned in Yann Martel's novel *The Life of Pi*, in which they are described by the protagonist's father as being among the most dangerous animals in his zoo.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Historically, one of the main threats to the Asiatic black bear populations in Pakistan was the capture of cubs to use in bear dancing and baiting for entertainment in streets and villages, especially for tourists.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Although usually shy and cautious animals, Asian black bears are more aggressive towards humans than the brown bears of Eurasia and American black bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Macdonald theorizes that this greater aggression is an adaptation to being sympatric with tigers.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] At the turn of the 20th century, a hospital in Srinagar, Kashmir received dozens of Asian black bear victims annually.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] When Asian black bears attack humans, they rear up on their hind legs and knock victims over with their front paws.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Then they bite them on an arm or leg and snap on the victim's head, this being the most dangerous part of the attack.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bear attacks have been increasing in Kashmir since the Kashmir conflict.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In November 2009, in the Kulgam district of Indian-administered Kashmir, an Asian black bear attacked four insurgents after discovering them in its den, and killed two of them.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In India, attacks on humans have been increasing yearly, and have occurred largely in the northwestern and western Himalayan region.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the Chamba District of Himachal Pradesh, the number of Asian black bear attacks on humans has gradually increased from 10 in 1988–89 to 21 in 1991–92.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] There are no records of predation on humans by Asian black bears in Russia, and no conflicts have been documented in Taiwan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bear attacks on humans were reported from Junbesi in Langtang National Park, Nepal in 2005, and occurred in villages as well as in the surrounding forest.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Nine people were killed by Asian black bears in Japan between 1979 and 1989.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In September 2009, an Asian black bear attacked a group of 9 tourists, seriously injuring four of them at a bus station in the built-up area of Takayama, Gifu.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The majority of attacks tend to occur when Asian black bears are encountered suddenly, and in close quarters.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Because of this, Asian black bears are generally considered more dangerous than brown bears, which live in more open spaces and are thus less likely to be surprised by approaching humans.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] They are also likely to attack when protecting food.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] 2016 saw several attacks by Asian black bears in Japan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In May and June four people were killed by Asian black bears in Akita prefecture while picking bamboo shoots, and in August a female safari park worker in Gunma prefecture was killed when an Asian black bear climbed into her car and attacked her.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] According to a recent review, humans killed ca.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] 50/100 individuals of the Himalayan black bear between 1998 and 2023 in Pakistan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] No data were reported for the Baluchistan black bear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] However, we are well aware that this value is greatly underestimated because this type of information is often intentionally concealed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the past, the farmers of the Himalayan lowlands feared Asian black bears more than any other pest, and would erect platforms in the fields, where watchmen would be posted at night and would beat drums to frighten off any interlopers.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] However, some Asian black bears would grow accustomed to the sound and encroach anyway.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Of 1,375 livestock kills examined in Bhutan, Asian black bears accounted for 8% of attacks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Livestock predation, overall, was greatest in the summer and autumn periods, which corresponded with a peak in cropping agriculture; livestock are turned out to pasture and forest during the cropping season and, subsequently, are less well-guarded than at other times.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Livestock killed by Asian black bears in Himachal Pradesh, India increased from 29 in 1988–1989 to 45 in 1992–1993.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the remoter areas of Japan, Asian black bears can be serious crop predators: the bears feed on cultivated bamboo shoots in spring, on plums, watermelons and corn in the summer, and on persimmons, sweet potatoes and rice in the autumn.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Japanese black bears are estimated to damage 3,000 bee hives annually.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] When feeding on large crops such as watermelons or pumpkins, Asian black bears will ignore the flesh and eat the seeds, thus adversely affecting future harvests.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears can girdle and kill trees by stripping their bark for the sap.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] This can cause serious economic problems in Asia's valuable timber forests.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the late 1970s, 400–1,200 hectares (990–2,970 acres) of land had been affected by Asian black bears bark-stripping Japanese conifers.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] There is evidence that 70-year-old conifers (commanding the highest market values) may also have been bark-stripped.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears will prey on livestock if their natural food is in poor supply.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] They have been known to attack bullocks, either killing them outright, or eating them alive.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Along with sun bears, Asian black bears are the most typically used species in areas where bears are used either in performances or as pets.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears have an outstanding learning ability in captivity, and are among the most common species used in circus acts.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears are easily tamed, and can be fed with rice, maize, sweet potatoes, cassavas, pumpkins, ripe fruit, animal fat and sweet foods.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Keeping captive Asian black bears is popular in China, especially due to the belief that milking the bear's gall bladder leads to quick prosperity.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears are also popular as pets in Vietnam.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] — *The Great and Small Game of India, Burma, and Tibet* p.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The book also describes a second method of black bear hunting involving the beating of small patches of forest, when the bears march out in single file.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] However, black bears were rarely hunted for sport, because of the poor quality of their fur and the ease by which they could be shot in trees, or stalked, as their hearing was poor.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Although easy to track and shoot, Asian black bears were known by British sportsmen to be extremely dangerous when injured.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Burton wrote of how many sportsmen had been killed by Asian black bears after failing to make direct hits.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Today, Asian black bears are only legally hunted for sport in Japan and Russia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In Russia, 75–100 Asian black bears are legally harvested annually, though 500 a year are reportedly harvested illegally.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] After the introduction of Buddhism in Japan, which prohibited the killing of animals, the Japanese compromised by devising different strategies in hunting bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Some, such as the inhabitants of the Kiso area in the Nagano Prefecture, prohibited the practice altogether, while others developed rituals in order to placate the spirits of killed bears.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In some Japanese hunting communities, Asian black bears lacking the white chest mark are considered sacred.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the Akita Prefecture, bears lacking the mark were known by *matagi* huntsmen as *minaguro* ('all-black') or *munaguro* ('black-chested'), and were also considered messengers of **yama no kami**.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] If such a bear was shot, the huntsman would offer it to **yama no kami**, and give up hunting from that time on.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Similar beliefs were held in Nagano, where the completely black Asian black bears were termed *nekoguma*, 'cat-bear'.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] *Matagi* communities believed that killing an Asian black bear in the mountains would result in a bad storm, which was linked to the belief that bear spirits could affect weather.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The *matagi* would generally hunt Asian black bears in spring or from late autumn to early winter, before they hibernated.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In mountain regions, Asian black bears were hunted by driving them upland to a waiting hunter, who would then shoot it.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Bear hunting expeditions were preceded by rituals, and could last up to two weeks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] After killing the bear, the *matagi* would pray for the bear's soul.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bear hunts in Japan are often termed *kuma taiji*, meaning 'bear conquest'.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The word *taiji* itself is often used in Japanese folklore to describe the slaying of monsters and demons.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Traditionally, the Atayal, Taroko, and Bunun people of Taiwan consider Asian black bears to be almost human in their behaviors, and thus unjust killing of bears is equated with murder and will cause misfortunes such as disease, death, or crop failure.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Bunun people call Asian black bears *aguman* or *duman*, which means 'devil'.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Traditionally, a Bunun hunter who has accidentally trapped an Asian black bear has to build a cottage in the mountains and cremate the bear within it.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The hunter must stay in the cottage alone, away from the village until the end of the millet harvest, as it is believed that the killing of an Asian black bear will cause the millet crop to burn black.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the Tungpu area, Asian black bears are considered animals of the "third category": animals with the most remote relationship to humans and whose activity is restricted outside human settlements.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Therefore, when Asian black bears encroach upon human settlements, they are considered ill omens.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In this situation, the community can either destroy the trespassing bears or settle somewhere else.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] The Rukai and Paiwan people are permitted to hunt Asian black bears, though they believe that doing so will curse the hunters involved: Rukai people believe that hunting Asian black bears can result in disease.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Children are forbidden from eating bear meat, which is itself not permitted to be taken within homes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Asian black bears have been hunted for their body parts in China since the Stone Age.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the 19th century, its fur was considered of low value.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Grease was the only practical use for their carcasses in British India, and bears living near villages were considered ideal, as they were almost invariably fatter than forest-dwelling ones.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] In the former USSR, the Asian black bear yielded fur, meat and fat of greater quality than those of the brown bear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Today, bile is in demand, as it supposedly cures various diseases, treats the accumulation of blood below the skin, and counters toxic effects.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-black-bear-p02] Products also include bone 'glue' and fat, both used in traditional medicine and consumed as a tonic.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The **Asian golden cat** (***Catopuma temminckii***) is a medium-sized wild cat native to the northeastern Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia and China.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It has been listed as Vulnerable on the IUCN Red List since 2025, and is threatened by poaching and habitat destruction, since Southeast Asian forests are undergoing the world's fastest regional deforestation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The Asian golden cat's scientific name honours Coenraad Jacob Temminck.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It is also called **Temminck's cat** and **Asiatic golden cat**.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Although briefly classified under the genus *Pardofelis* in 2007, a taxonomic revision determined that this species is retained in the genus *Catopuma*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] This decision was based on morphological analysis showing that its skull structure, as well as the characteristics of its legs and tail, differ from other species within the genus *Pardofelis*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It was subordinated to the genus *Catopuma* proposed by Nikolai Severtzov in 1853.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] This recognition was based on molecular genetic analysis that identified Kra Isthmus as the geographic barrier separating them.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Phylogenetic analysis of the nuclear DNA in tissue samples from all Felidae species revealed that the evolutionary radiation of the Felidae began in Asia in the Miocene around 14.45 to 8.38 million years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] All these species are grouped within the bay cat lineage.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The divergence between the Asian golden cat and the bay cat is estimated to have occurred during the late Pliocene, approximately 3.16 million years ago, which is more recent than previous estimates.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] This process was driven by rising sea levels that submerged the Kra Isthmus, geographically dividing mainland Southeast Asia from the Sunda Shelf and diverging the two species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The southern population located on the Sunda Shelf evolved into the bay cat, becoming highly dependent on tropical rainforest refugia that shrank due to climate change during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In contrast, the northern population in mainland Southeast Asia evolved into the more adaptable Asian golden cat, which subsequently expanded southward to the Sunda Shelf such as Sumatra and the Malay Peninsula by utilizing land bridges available during the Pleistocene glacial periods.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The difference in their coat colors highlights this evolutionary split.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] While the bay cat developed a more neutral camouflage adapted to life in a rainforest ecosystem, the Asian golden cat evolved a brighter and more varied coat to match its highly diverse range of environments.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Genetic analysis reveals very low nucleotide diversity across Asian golden cat populations.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Following this near-extinction event, the Asian golden cat underwent continuous population expansion gradually repopulating regions outside of Indochina.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] While mainland populations remained highly polymorphic, displaying a wide variety of coat colors and patterns, the newly established populations south of the Kra Isthmus are predominantly reddish.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The Asian golden cat is a medium-sized cat with a head-to-body length of 66–105 cm (26–41 in), with a 40–57 cm (16–22 in) long tail, and is 56 cm (22 in) tall at the shoulder.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Its weight ranges from 9 to 16 kg (20 to 35 lb), which is about two or three times that of a domestic cat (*Felis catus*).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The size of the tail is around one third and half of the body size.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It exhibits sexual dimorphism, with females being smaller than males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The Asian golden cat has facial markings featuring white stripes edged in dark brown or black that stretch from the nose across the cheeks, highlight the inner corners of the eyes, and cross the top of its head.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] These variations include the distinct morphs golden, cinnamon, brown, spotted, brown, reddish-brown, gray, and black.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It was also recorded in Bukit Rimbang Bukit Baling Wildlife Sanctuary and Kerinci Seblat National Park, Sumatra.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It was also recorded in Virachey National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Cinnamon morphs were recorded in Dibang Valley, Eaglenest Wildlife Sanctuary Yarlung Tsangpo Grand Canyon, Jigme Singye Wangchuck National Park Sylhet Division. and Torsa Strict Nature Reserve.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Gray morphs have been recorded in Bumthang District and the eastern Himalayas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Reddish brown morphs were recorded in Sumatra in 1872 and recorded again multiple times in Kerinci Seblat National Park on 2001 and 2013.It was also recorded in Kingpao village, Tuensang district.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In China, the morph was recorded in southern Yunnan and eastern Himalaya.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It was recorded in Wangchuck Centennial National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] An Asian golden cat with large rosettes on shoulders, flanks and hips was described for the first time based on a specimen from China in 1872.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] This morph was recorded in China at Hengduan Mountains and Eastern Himalayas, Bhutan in Bumthang District, Phrumsengla National Park and Jigme Singye Wangchuck National Park and in Buxa Tiger Reserve.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The Asian golden cat ranges from eastern Nepal, northeastern India and Bhutan to northeastern Bangladesh, to Myanmar, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, southern China, Malaysia and Sumatra.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It prefers forest habitats interspersed with rocky areas and inhabits dry deciduous, subtropical moist evergreen and tropical rainforests.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Since an individual was caught alive in 1831 in Nepal, the country was thought to be the westernmost part of the Asian golden cat's range.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In the 21st century, it was photographed in the country in May 2009 in Makalu Barun National Park at an elevation of 2,517 m (8,258 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In February 2019, it was also recorded in Gaurishankar Conservation Area at an elevation of 2,540 m (8,330 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Bangladesh, it was recorded in September 2021 in Rema-Kalenga Wildlife Sanctuary.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Bhutan's Jigme Singye Wangchuck National Park, it was recorded by camera traps at an elevation of 3,738 m (12,264 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In China, it was recorded in protected areas in the Qinling and Minshan Mountains between 2004 and 2009.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In northern Myanmar, it was recorded in Hkakaborazi National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In 2015, it was recorded for the first time in the hill forests of Karen State.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Thailand, it was recorded in Khao Yai National Park and Khlong Nakha Wildlife Sanctuary.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Vietnam, it was recorded in Pu Hoat Nature Reserve.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Laos, it inhabits bamboo regrowth, scrub and degraded forest from the Mekong plains to at least 1,100 m (3,600 ft).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Malaysia, it was recorded in a state forest in Merapoh in 2021.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Results of surveys in Sumatra indicated that it is more common than sympatric small cats, suggesting that it is more numerous than thought before the turn of the 21st century.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It has been recorded in Kerinci Seblat, Gunung Leuser and Bukit Barisan Selatan National Parks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Asian golden cats are territorial and solitary.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Previous observations suggested that they are primarily nocturnal, but a field study on two radio-collared specimens revealed arrhythmic activity patterns dominated by crepuscular and diurnal activity peaks, with much less activity late at night.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] However, based on a 2026 camera-trapping study, the species has a flexible daily schedule, with crepuscular and nocturnal peaks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It also detected that their average independent detection timestamp is recorded at 23:23 h.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In the study, the male's territory was 47.7 km2 (18.4 sq mi) in size and increased by more than 15% during the rainy season.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The female's territory was 32.6 km2 (12.6 sq mi) in size.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Both cats traveled between only 55 m (180 ft) to more than 9 km (5.6 mi) in a day, and were more active in July than in March.Asian golden cats recorded in northeast India were active during the day with activity peaks around noon.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Asian golden cats can climb trees when necessary.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] They hunt birds, hares, rodents, reptiles, and small ungulates such as muntjacs and young sambar deer.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] They are capable of bringing down prey much larger than themselves, such as domestic water buffalo calves.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In the mountains of Sikkim, Asian golden cats reportedly prey on ghoral.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Captive Asian golden cats kill small prey with the nape bite typical of cats.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] They also pluck birds larger than pigeons before beginning to feed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Their vocalizations include hissing, spitting, meowing, purring, growling, and gurgling.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Other methods of communication observed in captive Asian golden cats include scent marking, urine spraying, raking trees and logs with claws, and rubbing of the head against various objects – much like a domestic cat.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Not much is known about the reproductive behavior of this rather elusive cat in the wild.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Most of what is known has been learned from cats in captivity.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Female Asian golden cats are sexually mature between 18 and 24 months, while males mature at 24 months.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Females come into estrus every 39 days, at which time they leave markings and seek contact with the male by adopting receptive postures.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] During intercourse, the male will seize the skin of the neck of the female with his teeth.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] After a gestation period of 78 to 80 days, the female gives birth in a sheltered place to a litter of one to three kittens.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The kittens weigh 220 to 250 g (7.8 to 8.8 oz) at birth, but triple in size over the first eight weeks of life.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] They are born already possessing the adult coat pattern and open their eyes after six to twelve days.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In captivity, they live for up to twenty years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The Asian golden cat inhabits some of the fastest developing countries in the world, where it is increasingly threatened by habitat destruction following deforestation, along with a declining ungulate prey base.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Sumatra, it has been reported killed in revenge for preying on poultry.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Southeast Asia and China, it is threatened by poaching for the illegal wildlife trade.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] This trade has the greatest potential to do maximum harm in minimal time.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Asian golden cats are poached mainly for their fur.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Myanmar, 111 body parts from at least 110 individuals were observed in four designatedbetween 1991 and 2006.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Numbers were significantly greater than those of non-threatened species.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Among the observed skins was one with rosettes.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Three of the surveyed markets are situated on international borders with China and Thailand and cater to international buyers, although the Asian golden cat is completely protected under the country's national legislation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Effective implementation and enforcement of CITES is considered inadequate.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The Asian golden cat is included in CITES Appendix I and fully protected over most of its range.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Hunting is prohibited in Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Nepal, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] No information about protection status is available from Cambodia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Bhutan, it is protected only within the boundaries of protected areas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] It is listed as Vulnerable on the IUCN Red List, with a global population estimated at fewer than 10,000 individuals.The Office of Natural Resources and Environmental Policy and Planning of Thailand also listed the Asian golden cat as vulnerable.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In Nagaland's Peren district, an indigenous and community conserved area has been inaugurated for the conservation of the Asian Golden cat in May 2026.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] As of December 2008, there were 20 Asian golden cats in eight European zoos participating in the European Endangered Species Programme.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The pair in the German Wuppertal Zoo successfully bred in 2007, and in July 2008, two siblings were born and mother-reared.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In 2008, a female kitten was also born in the French Parc des Félins.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The species is also kept in the Singapore Zoo.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In China, the Asian golden cat is thought to be a kind of leopard and is known as "rock cat" or "yellow leopard".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Different colour phases have different names; those with black fur are called "inky leopards", and those with spotted coats are called "sesame leopards".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In some regions of Thailand, the Asian golden cat is called *seua fai* (Thai: เสือไฟ, lit.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] According to a regional legend, the burning of an Asian golden cat's fur drives tigers away.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Eating the flesh is believed to have the same effect.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] The Karen people believe that carrying a single hair of the cat is sufficient.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] Many indigenous people believe the cat to be fierce, but in captivity it has been known to be docile and tranquil.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-golden-cat] In southern Thailand, it is called *kang kude* (Thai: คางคูด) and believed to be a fierce animal that can hurt or eat livestock and larger animals such as Asian elephants.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The **Asiatic lion** is a lion that belongs to the subspecies *Panthera leo leo*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The surviving population of these lions is restricted to the Indian state of Gujarat.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It is classified as endangered in the IUCN Red List, is included on CITES Appendix I, and is legally protected in India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Phylogeographic analysis reveal that the Asiatic lion is genetically closely related to the North and West African lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The adult males measure up to 120 cm (47 in) in shoulder height and weigh about 160 kg (350 lb), making them slightly smaller than large African lions but similar to Central African populations.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic lion has a ruddy-tawny to sandy grey fur, a distinctive longitudinal skin fold along its belly, and a larger tail tuft.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The males are distinguishable from the females by the presence of manes, though they are shorter and sparser than the African counterparts.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It also differs from the African lion in skull structure, having a stronger sagittal crest, shorter post-orbital area, and often divided infraorbital foramina.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The first scientific description of the Asiatic lion published in 1826 was based on a specimen from Persia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Until the 19th century, it ranged from Saudi Arabia, eastern Turkey, Iran, Mesopotamia and southern Pakistan to Central India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Since the turn of the 20th century, its range has been restricted to the Gir National Park and its surrounding areas in Western India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Indian population, which numbered only 411 individuals in 2010, has steadily increased since then.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 2015, the lion population was estimated at 523 individuals, which increased to 650 in 2017 and 674 by 2023.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] As of 2025, there were an estimated 891 lions in the wild.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Since the mid-1990s, due to increase in the Asiatic lion population, about a third resided outside the protected area, and the conflict between local residents and the lions have increased.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Male Asiatic lions are often solitary or form small coalitions of up to three, while females live in larger prides with the cubs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Males and females usually only associate briefly during mating.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In the Gir National Park, they are mainly nocturnal and defend territories, whose size varies.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They prefer dense vegetation or shaded riverine habitats in dry periods.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They prefer large prey and commonly hunt chital, sambar, nilgai, and other livestock, and may also scavenge or prey on species such as wild boar and mugger crocodiles near water sources.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 2017, the Asiatic lion was subsumed to *P. l. leo* due to close morphological and molecular genetic similarities with Barbary lion specimens.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] However, several scientists continue using *P. l. persica* for the Asiatic lion.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] A standardised haplogroup phylogeny supports that the Asiatic lion is not a distinct subspecies, and that it represents a haplogroup of the northern *P. l. leo*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Lions first dispersed out of Africa at least 1 million years ago, giving rise to the Eurasian *Panthera fossilis* which later evolved into *Panthera spelaea* (both having the common name "cave lions"), which became extinct around 14,000 years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Genetic analysis of *P. spelaea* indicates that it represented a distinct species that genetically diverged from the modern lion around 500,000 – 1 million years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1976, fossil lion remains were reported from Pleistocene deposits in West Bengal.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] A fossil carnassial excavated from Batadomba Cave indicates that lions inhabited Sri Lanka during the Late Pleistocene.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] This population may have become extinct around 39,000 years ago, before the arrival of humans in Sri Lanka.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Results of a phylogeographic analysis based on mtDNA sequences of lions from across the global range, including now extinct populations like Barbary lions, indicates that sub-Saharan African lions are phylogenetically basal to all modern lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] These findings support an African origin of modern lion evolution with a probable centre in East and Southern Africa.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It is likely that lions migrated from there to West Africa, eastern North Africa and via the periphery of the Arabian Peninsula into Turkey, southern Europe and northern India during the last 20,000 years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Sahara, Congolian rainforests and the Great Rift Valley are natural barriers to lion dispersal.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Genetic markers of 357 samples from captive and wild lions from Africa and India were examined.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic lion is genetically closer to North and West African lions than to the group comprising East and Southern African lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The two groups probably diverged about 186,000–128,000 years ago.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It is thought that the Asiatic lion remained connected to North and Central African lions until gene flow was interrupted due to extinction of lions in Western Eurasia and the Middle East during the Holocene.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Asiatic lions are less genetically diverse than African lions, which may be the result of a founder effect in the recent history of the remnant population in the Gir forest.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic lion's fur ranges in colour from ruddy-tawny, heavily speckled with black, to sandy or buffish grey, sometimes with a silvery sheen in certain lighting.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Males have only moderate mane growth at the top of the head, so that their ears are always visible.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The mane is scanty on the cheeks and throat, where it is only 10 cm (4 in) long.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] About half of Asiatic lions' skulls from the Gir forest have divided infraorbital foramina, whereas African lions have only one foramen on either side.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The sagittal crest is more strongly developed, and the post-orbital area is shorter than in African lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It differs from the African lion by a larger tail tuft and less inflated auditory bullae.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The most striking morphological character of the Asiatic lion is a longitudinal fold of skin running along its belly.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Two lions in Gir forest measured 1.98 m (6 ft 6 in) from head to body with a 0.79–0.89 m (31–35 in) long tail of and total lengths of 2.82–2.87 m (9 ft 3 in – 9 ft 5 in).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Gir lion is similar in size to the Central African lion, and smaller than large African lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] An adult male Asiatic lion weighs 160.1 kg (353 lb) on average with the limit being 190 kg (420 lb); a wild female weighs 100 to 130 kg (220 to 285 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Colour and development of manes in male lions varies between regions, among populations and with age of lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In general, the Asiatic lion differs from the African lion by a less developed mane.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The manes of most lions in ancient Greece and Asia Minor were also less developed and did not extend to below the belly, sides or ulnas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Lions with such smaller manes were also known in the Syrian region, Arabian Peninsula and Egypt.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The confirmed record for the total length of a male Asiatic lion is 2.92 m (9 ft 7 in), including the tail.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Mughal emperor Jahangir allegedly speared a lion in the 1620s that measured 3.10 m (10 ft 2 in) and weighed 306 kg (675 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1841, English traveller Austen Henry Layard, who accompanied hunters in Khuzestan, Iran, sighted a lion which "had done much damage in the plain of Ram Hormuz," before one of his companions killed it.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] He described it as being "unusually large and of very dark brown colour", with some parts of its body being almost black.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1935, a British admiral claimed to have sighted a maneless lion near Quetta in Pakistan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In Saurashtra's Gir forest, an area of 1,412.1 km2 (545.2 sq mi) was declared as a sanctuary for Asiatic lion conservation in 1965.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] This sanctuary and the surrounding areas are the only habitats supporting the Asiatic lion.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] After 1965, a national park was established covering an area of 258.71 km2 (99.89 sq mi) where human activity is not allowed.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In the surrounding sanctuary only Maldharis have the right to take their livestock for grazing.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Lions inhabit remnant forest habitats in the two hill systems of Gir and Girnar that comprise Gujarat's largest tracts of tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests, thorny forest and savanna, and provide valuable habitat for a diverse flora and fauna.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Five protected areas currently exist to protect the Asiatic lion: Gir National Park, Gir, Pania, Girnar, and Mitiyala Wildlife Sanctuaries.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The first three protected areas form the Gir Conservation Area, a 1,452 km2 (561 sq mi) large forest block that represents the core habitat of the lion population.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The other two sanctuaries Mitiyala and Girnar protect satellite areas within dispersal distance of the Gir Conservation Area.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] An additional sanctuary is being established in the nearby Barda Wildlife Sanctuary to serve as an alternative home for lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The drier eastern part is vegetated with acacia thorn savanna and receives about 650 mm (26 in) annual rainfall; rainfall in the west is higher at about 1,000 mm (39 in) per year.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lion population recovered from the brink of extinction to 411 individuals by 2010.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In that year, approximately 105 lions lived outside the Gir forest, representing a quarter of the entire lion population.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Dispersing sub-adults established new territories outside their natal prides, and as a result the satellite lion population has been increasing since 1995.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] By 2015, the total population had grown to an estimated 523 individuals, inhabiting an area of 7,000 km2 (2,700 sq mi) in the Saurashtra region., comprising 109 adult males, 201 adult females and 213 cubs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic Lion Census conducted in 2017 revealed about 650 individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] By 2020, at least six satellite populations had spread to eight districts in Gujarat and live in human-dominated areas outside the protected area network.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Lions living along the coast, as well as those between the coastline and the Gir forest, have larger individual ranges.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 2024 and 2025, lions began swimming to Diu Island, separated from the mainland of Gujarat by a narrow channel.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] These individuals were relocated to Gujarat on request of the Diu administration over concerns of disruption to human life, although conservationists protested the removal as unnecessary.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] During the Holocene, from around 6,500 years ago and possibly as early as 8,000 years ago, the lion colonised Southeast Europe including Bulgaria, Greece, parts of central and eastern Europe.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Analysis of remains of these lions suggests that they did not differ from today's Asiatic lion.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Historical records suggest that the lion became extinct in Europe during Classical antiquity, though it has been suggested that some may have survived as late as the Middle Ages in Ukraine.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic lion used to occur in Arabia, the Levant, Mesopotamia and Baluchistan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In South Caucasia, it was known since the Holocene and became extinct in the 10th century.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Until the middle of the 19th century, it survived in regions adjoining Mesopotamia and Syria, and was still sighted in the upper reaches of the Euphrates River in the early 1870s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] By the late 19th century, it had become extinct in Saudi Arabia and Turkey.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The last known lion in Iraq was killed on the lower Tigris in 1918.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Historical records in Iran indicate that it ranged from the Khuzestan Plain to Fars province at elevations below 2,000 m (6,600 ft) in steppe vegetation and pistachio-almond woodlands.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It was widespread in the country, but in the 1870s, it was sighted only on the western slopes of the Zagros Mountains, and in the forest regions south of Shiraz.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It served as the national emblem and appeared on the country's flag.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Some of the country's last lions were sighted in 1941 between Shiraz and Jahrom in Fars province, and in 1942, a lion was spotted about 65 km (40 mi) northwest of Dezful.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1944, the corpse of a lioness was found on the banks of the Karun River in Iran's Khuzestan province.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In India, the Asiatic lion occurred in Sind, Bahawalpur, Punjab, Gujarat, Rajasthan, Haryana, Bihar and eastward as far as Palamau and Rewa, Madhya Pradesh in the early 19th century.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It once ranged to Bangladesh in the east and up to Narmada River in the south.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Because of the lion's restricted distribution in India, Reginald Innes Pocock assumed that it arrived from Europe, entering southwestern Asia through Balochistan only recently, before humans started limiting its dispersal in the country.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The advent and increasing availability of firearms led to its local extirpation over large areas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Heavy hunting by British colonial officers and Indian rulers caused a steady and marked decline of lion numbers in the country.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Lions were exterminated in Palamau by 1814, in Baroda State, Hariana and Ahmedabad district in the 1830s, in Kot Diji and Damoh district in the 1840s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] During the Indian Rebellion of 1857, a British officer shot 300 lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The last lions of Gwalior and Rewah were shot in the 1860s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] One lion was killed near Allahabad in 1866.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The last lion of Mount Abu in Rajasthan was spotted in 1872.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] By the late 1870s, lions were extinct in Rajasthan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] By 1880, no lion survived in Guna, Deesa and Palanpur districts, and only about a dozen lions were left in Junagadh district.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] By the turn of the century, the Gir forest held the only Asiatic lion population in India, which was protected by the Nawab of Junagarh in his private hunting grounds.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Male Asiatic lions are solitary, or associate with up to three males, forming a loose pride.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Pairs of males rest, hunt and feed together, and display marking behaviour at the same sites.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Females associate with up to twelve other females, forming a stronger pride together with their cubs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Female and male lions usually associate only for a few days when mating, but rarely live and feed together.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Results of a radio telemetry study indicate that annual home ranges of male lions vary from 144 to 230 km2 (56 to 89 sq mi) in dry and wet seasons.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Home ranges of females are smaller, varying between 67 and 85 km2 (26 and 33 sq mi).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] During hot and dry seasons, they favour densely vegetated and shady riverine habitats, where prey species also congregate.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Coalitions of males defend home ranges containing one or more female prides.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Together, they hold a territory for a longer time than single lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Males in coalitions of three to four individuals exhibit a pronounced hierarchy with one male dominating the others.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lions in Gir National Park often spend the day resting and are more active at twilight and by night.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Studies on captive Asiatic lions also indicated that they spent nearly most of the day time lying down or inactive, with juveniles spending slightly lesser time on inactive behaviours.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The activity increased towards the twilight hours, when the lions spend more time on feeding, and walking.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They also sometimes engage in self and social grooming.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lions also showed various levels of increased activity in response to perceived threat or other stimuli.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In general, lions prefer large prey species within a weight range of 190 to 550 kg (420 to 1,210 lb), irrespective of their availability.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In the Gir forest, the lions' prey includes chital (*Axis axis*), nilgai (*Boselaphus tragocamelus*), sambar (*Rusa unicolor*), and less frequently wild boar (*Sus scrofa*).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They most commonly kill chital, which weighs around 50 kg (110 lb) on average.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They prey on sambar deer when the latter descend from the hills during the summer.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Outside the protected area where wild prey species do not occur, Domestic cattle (*Bos taurus*), and water buffalo (*Bubalus bubalis*) have historically formed a major component of the Asiatic lions' diet in the Gir region.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They also rarely prey on dromedary (*Camelus dromedarius*).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They regularly visit specific sites within the protected area to scavenge on dead livestock dumped by Maldhari livestock herders.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] During dry, hot months, they have also been noticed to prey on mugger crocodiles (*Crocodylus palustris*) on the banks of Kamleshwar Dam.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1974, the Indian forest department estimated the wild ungulate population of the Gir forest at 9,650 individuals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The populations of domestic buffalo and cattle declined from 24,250 individuals in the 1970s declined to 12,500 by the mid-1980s in the Gir Conservation Area, largely following the resettlement of people.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Though, the population of livestock later increased to 23,440 animals by 2010, the Asiatic lions had shifted their predation patterns by then, and very few livestock kills occurred within the sanctuary.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Most of these kills occur in peripheral villages instead, and predation records indicate that the lions killed on average 2,023 livestock annually between 2005 and 2009, and an additional 696 individuals in satellite areas in around the Gir forest.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lions generally kill most prey less than 100 m (330 ft) away from water bodies.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They usually charge towards the prey from close range and generally jump on the backs of large prey to bring them down.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They might also trip the legs of smaller prey, and later use their powerful jaws to snap the animal's neck or to strangle it to death.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] They later drag the hunted carcasses into dense cover.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The nocturnal behaviour of the lions shows a high temporal overlap with its prey such as nilgai, sambar, and wild boar.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Females share large carcasses among each other, but seldom with males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Dominant males consume about 47% more from kills than their coalition partners.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Aggression between partners increases when coalitions are large, but kills are small.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In the Gir forest, the lionesses often made kills at times when they were least likely to be encountered by males, to prevent the carcass being shared with or stolen by males.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The level of kleptoparasitism was lower in Asiatic lions, compared to their African counterparts.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lions spend more time eating hunted prey, rather than scavenged carcasses.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Asiatic lions mate foremost between October and November.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] During these days, they usually do not hunt, but only drink water.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The average interval between births is 24 months, unless cubs die due to infanticide by adult males or because of diseases and injuries.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Cubs become independent at the age of about two years.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Subadult males leave their natal pride latest at the age of three years and become nomads until they establish their own territory.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Dominant males mate more frequently than their coalition partners.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] During a study carried out between December 2012 and December 2016, three females were observed switching mating partners in favour of the dominant male.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Monitoring of more than 70 mating events showed that females mated with males of several rivaling prides that shared their home ranges, and that these males were tolerant toward the same cubs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Only new males that entered the female territories killed unfamiliar cubs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Young females mated foremost with males within their home ranges.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Older females selected males at the periphery of their home ranges.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic lion currently exists as a single subpopulation, and is thus vulnerable to extinction from unpredictable events, such as an epidemic or large forest fire.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] There are indications of poaching incidents in recent years, as well as reports that organized poacher gangs have switched attention from local Bengal tigers to the Gujarat lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] There have also been a number of drowning incidents, after lions fell into wells.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Prior to the resettlement of Maldharis, the Gir forest was heavily degraded and used by livestock, which competed with and restricted the population sizes of native ungulates.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Various studies reveal tremendous habitat recovery and increases in wild ungulate populations following the resettlement of Maldharis since the 1970s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Nearly 25 lions in the vicinity of Gir forest were found dead in October 2018.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Four of them had died because of canine distemper virus, the same virus that had also killed several lions in the Serengeti.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Since the mid-1990s, the Asiatic lion population has increased to an extent that by 2015, about a third resided outside the protected area.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Hence, conflict between local residents and wildlife also increased.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Local people protect their crops from nilgai, wild boar, and other herbivores by using electrical fences that are powered with high voltage.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Some consider the presence of predators a benefit, as they keep the herbivore population in check.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] But some also fear the lions, and killed several in retaliation for attacks on livestock.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In July 2012, a lion dragged a man from the veranda of his house and killed him about 50–60 km (31–37 mi) from Gir National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] This was the second attack by a lion in this area, six months after a 25-year-old man was attacked and killed in Dhodadar.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In the 1950s, biologists advised the Indian government to re-establish at least one wild population in the Asiatic lion's former range to ensure the population's reproductive health and to prevent it from being affected by an outbreak of an epidemic.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1957, one male and two female wild-caught Asiatic lions were set free in the sanctuary.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] This population comprised 11 animals in 1965, which all disappeared thereafter.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic Lion Reintroduction Project to find an alternative habitat for reintroducing Asiatic lions was pursued in the early 1990s.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Biologists from the Wildlife Institute of India assessed several potential translocation sites for their suitability regarding existing prey population and habitat conditions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Palpur-Kuno Wildlife Sanctuary in northern Madhya Pradesh was ranked as the most promising location, followed by Sita Mata Wildlife Sanctuary and Darrah National Park.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Until 2000, 1,100 families from 16 villages had been resettled from the Palpur-Kuno Wildlife Sanctuary, and another 500 families from eight villages were expected to be resettled.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] With this resettlement scheme the protected area was expanded by 345 km2 (133 sq mi).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Gujarat state officials resisted the relocation, since it would make the Gir Sanctuary lose its status as the world's only home of the Asiatic lion.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Gujarat raised a number of objections to the proposal, and thus the matter went before the Indian Supreme Court.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In April 2013, the Indian Supreme Court ordered the Gujarat state to send some of their Gir lions to Madhya Pradesh to establish a second population there.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Gujarat state government has resisted relocation of lions to other states.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1977, Iran attempted to restore its lion population by transporting Gir lions to Arzhan National Park, but the project met resistance from the local population, and thus it was not implemented.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] However, this did not stop Iran from seeking to bring back the lion.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In February 2019, Tehran Zoological Garden obtained a male Asiatic lion from Bristol Zoo in the United Kingdom, followed in June by a female from Dublin Zoo.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] There are hopes for them to successfully reproduce.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Until the late 1990s, captive Asiatic lions in Indian zoos were haphazardly interbred with African lions confiscated from circuses, leading to genetic pollution in the captive Asiatic lion stock.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Once discovered, this led to the complete shutdown of the European and American endangered species breeding programs for Asiatic lions, as its founder animals were captive-bred Asiatic lions originally imported from India and were ascertained to be intraspecific hybrids of African and Asian lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] DNA fingerprinting studies of Asiatic lions have helped in identifying individuals with high genetic variability, which can be used for conservation breeding programs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 2006, the Central Zoo Authority of India stopped breeding Indian-African cross lions stating that "hybrid lions have no conservation value and it is not worth to spend resources on them".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Now only pure native Asiatic lions are bred in India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1972 the Sakkarbaug Zoo sold a pair of young pure-stock lions to the Fauna Preservation Society; which decided they would be accommodated at the Jersey Wildlife Trust where it was hoped to begin a captive breeding programme.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic lion International Studbook was initiated in 1977, followed in 1983 by the North American Species Survival Plan (SSP).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The North American population of captive Asiatic lions was composed of descendants of five founder lions, three of which were pure Asian and two were African or African-Asian hybrids.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lions kept in the framework of the SSP consisted of animals with high inbreeding coefficients.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In the early 1990s, three European zoos imported pure Asiatic lions from India: London Zoo obtained two pairs; the Zürich Zoologischer Garten one pair; and the Korkeasaari Zoo in Helsinki one male and two females.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] In 1994, the European Endangered Species Programme (EEP) for Asiatic lions was initiated.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The European Association of Zoos and Aquaria (EAZA) published the first European Studbook in 1999.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] By 2005, there were 80 Asiatic lions kept in the EEP – the only captive population outside of India.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] As of 2009, more than 100 Asiatic lions were kept within the EEP.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The SSP had not resumed; pure-bred Asiatic lions are needed to form a new founder population for breeding in American zoos.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Neolithic cave paintings of lions were found in Bhimbetka rock shelters in Central India, which are at least 30,000 years old.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lion was a prominent symbol in various cultures and countries in South and East Asia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The symbol of the lion is closely tied to the Persian people, and Achaemenid kings carried the symbol of the lion on their thrones and garments.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The name 'Shir', also pronounced 'Sher' (Persian: شیر), is a part of the names of many places in Iran and Central Asia, like those of city of Shiraz and the Sherabad River, and had been adopted into other languages, like Hindi.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The *Shir-va-Khorshid* (Persian: شیر و خورشید, "Lion and Sun") is one of the most prominent symbols of Iran, dating back to the Safavid dynasty, and was used on the flag of Iran until 1979.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Lions are depicted on vases dating to about 2600 BCE that were excavated near Lake Urmia in Iran.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lion was an important symbol in Ancient Iraq and is depicted in a stone relief at Nineveh in the Mesopotamian Plain.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Lion of Babylon is an ancient Babylonian symbol, which represented the King of Babylon.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lion of Babylon is a statue at the Ishtar Gate in Babylon.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lion has an important association with the figure Gilgamesh, as demonstrated in the Epic of Gilgamesh.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lion featured in the coat of arms of Iraq in the early 20th century and the Iraqi national football team is nicknamed "Lions of Mesopotamia".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Asiatic lion has significance in Arab and Islamic culture.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Other Arabic words for 'lion' include *asad* (Arabic: أَسَد) and *sabaʿ* (Arabic: سَبَع).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Ali ibn Abi Talib and Hamzah ibn Abdul-Muttalib were given titles like *Asad Allah* (Arabic: أَسَد ٱلله, lit.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] An Arabic toponym for the city of Beersheba (Arabic: بِئر ٱلسَّبَع) can mean "Spring of the Lion".
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Lion of Judah is a Jewish national and cultural symbol, traditionally regarded as the symbol of the tribe of Judah.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] It is mentioned in the blessing given by Jacob to his fourth son, Judah, in the Book of Genesis of the Hebrew Bible.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The lion makes appearances in the Bible, most notably as having fought Samson in the Book of Judges.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] The Nemean lion of pre-literate Greek myth is associated with the Labours of Hercules.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] A Bronze Age statue of a lion from either southern Italy or southern Spain from around 1000–1200 years BCE, the "Mari-Cha Lion", was exhibited at the Louvre Abu Dhabi.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] *Damnatio ad bestias* was a form of Roman capital punishment where the condemned person was killed by wild animals, usually lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Games held at the Colosseum included events where gladiators fought lions.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-lion] Lion hunting was practised in the Caucasus by both locals and foreigners.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The **Asiatic wildcat** (***Felis lybica ornata***), also known as the **Indian desert cat**, is an African wildcat subspecies that occurs from the eastern Caspian Sea north to Kazakhstan, into western India, western China and southern Mongolia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] There is no information on current status or population numbers across the Asiatic wildcat's range as a whole, but populations are thought to be declining.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In the 1940s, Reginald Innes Pocock reviewed the collection of wildcat skins and skulls in the Natural History Museum, London and subordinated all the spotted wildcat specimens to *Felis lybica*, arguing that size of skulls and teeth do not differ from those from African range countries.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The Asiatic wildcat's fur is light sandy coloured with small rounded spots on its upper body.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] These spots are solid and sharply defined, and do not occur in clusters.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The spots on the chest and abdomen are much larger and more blurred than on the back, and usually do not form transverse rows or stripes on the trunk.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The hairs along the spine are usually darker, forming a dark gray, brownish or ochreous band.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The upper lips and eyelids are light, pale yellow-white.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The facial region is of an intense gray colour, while the top of the head is covered with a dark gray coat.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In some individuals, the forehead is covered in dense clusters of brown spots.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] A narrow, dark brown stripe extends from the corner of the eye to the base of the ear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The lower neck, throat, neck, and the region between the forelegs are devoid of spots, or only with indistinct spots.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The underside is whitish, with a light gray, creamy or pale yellow tinge.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The tail is mostly the same colour as the back, with the addition of a dark and narrow stripe along the upper two-thirds of the tail; it appears thin, as the hairs are short and close-fitting.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The tip of the tail is black, with two to five black transverse rings above it.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The Asian wildcat has a long, tapering tail, always with a short black tip, and with spots at the base.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The forehead has a pattern of four well-developed black bands.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] A small but pronounced tuft of hair up to one cm long grows from the tip of each ear.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Paler forms of Asian wildcat live in drier areas and the darker, more heavily spotted and striped forms occur in more humid and wooded areas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The throat and ventral surfaces are whitish to light grey to cream, often with distinct white patches on the throat, chest and belly.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Throughout its range the Asian wildcat's coat is usually short, but the length of the fur can vary depending on the age of the animal and the season of the year.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Compared to the domestic cat, Asian wildcats have relatively longer legs.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Males are generally heavier than females.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Pakistan and India, wildcats have pale sandy yellow coats, marked with small spots that tend to lie in vertical lines down the trunk and flanks.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The wildcats of Central Asia have a more greyish-yellow or reddish background color, marked distinctly with small black or red-brown spots.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The spots are sometimes fused into stripes, especially in the Central Asian regions east of the Tian Shan Mountains.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The Asiatic wildcat weighs about 3–4 kg (6.6–8.8 lb).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The Caucasus is the transitional zone between the European wildcat to the north and west, and the Asiatic wildcat to the south and east.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In this region, the European wildcat is present in montane forest, and the Asiatic wildcat is present in the low-lying desert and semi-desert areas adjoining the Caspian Sea.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] It usually occurs in close proximity to water sources, but is also able to live year-round in waterless desert.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] It ranges up to 2,000 to 3,000 m (6,600 to 9,800 ft) in mountain areas with sufficient dense vegetation.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Snow depth limits the northern boundaries of its range in winter.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Iran, the Asiatic wildcat has been recorded in arid plains, lush forests, coastal areas and mountains, but not in extremely high elevations and deserts.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Afghanistan, the Asiatic wildcat has been recorded prior to 1973 in the central Hazarajat mountains and the steppe region, near Shibar Pass and Herat, and in Bamyan Province.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In India, the Asiatic wildcat inhabits the Thar Desert and is associated with scrub desert.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In 1999, it was still reported as common in the Rajasthani districts of Bikaner, Barmer, Jaisalmer, Pali and Nagaur.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Only four sightings were reported in the Thar Desert between 1999 and 2006.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] It has been recorded in Nauradehi Wildlife Sanctuary, in Madhya Pradesh and Mirzapur forests.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Pakistan, it was known from arid regions in the Sindh Province.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In the 1990s, wildcats were reported common and populations stable in the lowlands of Kazakhstan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] A pronounced loss of range has been documented in Azerbaijan.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Within China, the Asian wildcat is distributed in Xinjiang, Qinghai, Gansu, Ningxia, Shaanxi, and Inner Mongolia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Records from northern Tibet as well as Sichuan are questionable.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Prior to 1950, it was the most abundant cat in Xinjiang occurring along all major river basin systems and Taklimakan desert but later it got confined to three regions of southern Xinjiang only like the Bayingolin Mongol Autonomous Prefecture, Aksu and Hotan Prefectures.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] It was thought to decline rapidly in the Xinjiang desert region of China mainly because of excessive hunting for the pelt trade followed by shrinkage of its habitat due to cultivation, oil and gas exploration and excessive use of pesticides.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Asiatic wildcats are frequently observed in the daytime.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] They use rock crevices or burrows dug by other animals.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Turkmenistan, the Asiatic wildcat feed on great gerbils, Libyan jirds, Afghan voles, long-clawed ground squirrels, tolai hares, small birds like larks, lizards, beetles, and grasshoppers.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Near Repetek Biosphere State Reserve, the wildcat is responsible for destroying over 50% of nests made by desert finches, streaked scrub warblers, red-tailed warblers, and turtledoves.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In the Qarshi steppes of Uzbekistan, the wildcat's prey, in descending order of preference, includes great gerbils, Libyan jirds, jerboas, other rodents and passerine birds, reptiles, and insects.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Wildcats in eastern Kyzyl Kum have similar prey preferences, with the addition of tolai hares, Midday jirds, small five-toed jerboas, and steppe agamas.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Kyrgyzstan, the wildcat's primary prey varies from Tolai hares near Issyk Kul, pheasants in the Chu and Talas River valleys, and mouse-like rodents and gray partridges in the foothills.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Kazakhstan's lower Ili River, the wildcat mainly targets rodents, muskrats, and Tamarisk jird.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Occasionally, remains of young roe deer and wild boar are present in its faeces.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] After rodents, birds follow in importance, along with reptiles, fish, insects, eggs, grass stalks and nuts.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In the scrub habitat of western Rajasthan, they live largely on desert gerbils, but also hunt hares, rats, doves, gray partridges, sandgrouses, peafowl, bulbuls, Old World sparrows and eat eggs of ground birds.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] They have also been observed killing cobras, saw-scaled vipers, sand boas, geckos, scorpions and beetles.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Results of a feed item analysis of Asiatic wildcats in the Tarim Basin revealed that their primary prey was the Yarkand hare followed by Midday jird, long-eared jerboa, poultry and small bird, fish, five-toed pygmy jerboa, Agamid lizards and sand lizard.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The wildcat is highly parasitised by helminths.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Some wildcats in Georgia carry the helminth species *Hydatigera taeniaeformis*, *Diphyllobothrium mansoni*, *Toxocara mystax*, *Capillaria feliscati* and *Ancylostoma caninum*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Wildcats in Azerbaijan carry *Hydatigera krepkogorski* and *Toxocara mystax*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Transcaucasia, the majority of wildcats are infested by the tick *Ixodes ricinus*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In some summers, wildcats are infested with fleas of the genus *Ceratophyllus*, which they likely contract from brown rats.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] Female Asiatic wildcats mate quite often with domestic males, and hybrid offspring are frequently found near villages where wild females live.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] They have been hunted at large in Afghanistan; in 1977 over 1,200 pelts manufactured into different articles were on display in Kabul bazaars.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] The Asiatic wildcat is included on CITES Appendix II.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] It is protected in Turkmenistan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Mongolia, China and Russia.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/asiatic-wildcat] In Afghanistan, it has been placed on the country's first Protected Species List in 2009, banning all hunting and trading within the country, and is proposed as a priority species for future study.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/endangered-mammals-of-india] In India, mammals comprise 410 species, 186 genera, 45 families and 13 orders of which nearly 89 species are listed as threatened in the International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources (IUCN) Red List of Threatened Animals (IUCN 2006).
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/endangered-mammals-of-india] This includes two species that are locally extinct from India viz.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/endangered-mammals-of-india] *Acinonyx jubatus* and *Rhinoceros sondaicus*.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/endangered-mammals-of-india] The mammals are the class of vertebrate animals characterized by the presence of mammary glands, which in females produce milk for the nourishment of young; the presence of hair or fur; specialized teeth; the presence of a neocortex region in the brain; and endothermic or "warm-blooded" bodies.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/endangered-mammals-of-india] The brain regulates endothermic and circulatory system, including a four-chambered heart.
[src:endangered-mammals-of-india/endangered-mammals-of-india] Mammals encompass some 5,500 species (including Humans), distributed in about 1,200 genera, 152 families and up to 46 orders, though this varies with the classification scheme.
